{"title_page": "Castellane", "text_new": "{{For|the neighbourhood in [[Marseille]]|La Castellane}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name               = Castellane\n|commune status     = [[Subprefectures in France|Subprefecture]] and [[Communes of France|commune]]\n|image              = Fr- Castellane & Le Roc von oben.jpg\n|caption            = Castellane and Le Roc from above\n|image coat of arms = Blason Castellane.svg\n|arrondissement     = Castellane\n|canton             = Castellane\n|INSEE              = 04039\n|postal code        = 04120\n|mayor              = Jean-Pierre Terrien\n|term               = 2014\u20132020\n|intercommunality   = [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes Alpes Provence Verdon - Sources de Lumi\u00e8re|Alpes Provence Verdon \u2013 Sources de Lumi\u00e8re]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|43.8475|6.5139|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m        = 724\n|elevation min m    = 639\n|elevation max m    = 1761\n|area km2           = 117.79\n|population         = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date    = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}\n\n'''Castellane''' ({{IPA-fr|kast\u025blan}}; [[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]]: ''Castelana'') is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]] [[Departments of France|department]] in southeastern [[France]]. With about 1,600 inhabitants, Castellane has the distinction of being the least-populated sub-prefecture of France.\n\nIts inhabitants are referred to as ''Castellanais''.<ref>Roger Brunet, [http://tresordesregions.mgm.fr Canton of Castellane], ''Le Tr\u00e9sor des r\u00e9gions''</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCastellane is a very old city located upstream of the [[Verdon Gorge|Gorges du Verdon]]. The city is {{convert|724|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} [[above sea level]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Michel de La Torre |title= Alpes-de-Haute-Provence : le guide complet des 200 communes|location=Paris |publisher= Deslogis-Lacoste |work= Villes et villages de France |year=1989 |isbn=2-7399-5004-7}}</ref>\n\nThe Roc, or the Roc of Notre-Dame, overlooks the city from {{cvt|184|m|ft|0}} above.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Dichary|title=Castellane: \u00e0 l'aube des gorges du Verdon|publisher=Serre \u00c9diteur |location=Nice |year=1994 |language=French |trans-title=Castellane: At the Dawn of the Gorges of Verdon|isbn=978-2-86410-206-9 |page=7}}</ref> It has been occupied since the [[High Middle Ages]] and is a registered historical site. It can be accessed from the centre of town behind the old Church of St. Andrew. The walk takes about 25 minutes.\n[[File:Lac_de_Chaudanne.JPG|thumb|left|Lac de Chaudanne]]\nTwo reservoirs are located in the territory of Castellane:\n* [[Lac de Castillon|Lake Castillon]]\n* Lake Chaudanne, created by the dam of the same name, the {{Interlanguage link multi|Barrage de Chaudanne|fr}}.\nThe area has two [[water gap]]s: \n* the ''clue de Taulanne'' containing the [[Asse (river)|Asse de Blieux]] river and the [[Route Napol\u00e9on]] along its banks.\n* the ''clue de Chasteuil'', which contains the [[Verdon River|Verdon]] valley.\n[[File:Mobeye-\u00c9t\u00e9DesVilles-Castellane-366.jpg|thumb|left|Gorge of Castellane]]\nThe GR 4 hiking trail crosses through the town. The neighboring municipalities are:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Saint-Andr\u00e9-les-Alpes]]\n* [[Saint-Julien-du-Verdon]]\n* [[Demandolx]]\n* [[La Garde, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|La Garde]]\n* [[Ch\u00e2teauvieux, Var|Ch\u00e2teauvieux]]\n* [[Brenon]]\n* [[Le Bourguet]]\n* [[Trigance]]\n* [[Rougon]]\n* [[Blieux]]\n* [[Senez]]\n}}\n\n=== Climate ===\n\nCastellane features a [[mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: [[Hot-summer Mediterranean climate|Csa/Csb]]), bordering a cold [[humid continental climate|continental mediterraneran climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: [[Hot-summer humid continental climate|Dsa/Dsb]]). Summers are very hot and dry and winters are quite cold for a Mediterranean climate. Actually, Castellane's climate lays between two climates.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Digne-les-Bains, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, France\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|collapsed = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 22.8\n|Feb record high C = 23.7\n|Mar record high C = 25.8\n|Apr record high C = 27.6\n|May record high C = 31.8\n|Jun record high C = 35.6\n|Jul record high C = 37.3\n|Aug record high C = 37\n|Sep record high C = 33.4\n|Oct record high C = 29.7\n|Nov record high C = 23.3\n|Dec record high C = 20.3\n|year record high C = 37.3\n|Jan high C = 8.8\n|Feb high C = 10.7\n|Mar high C = 14\n|Apr high C = 15.9\n|May high C = 20.4\n|Jun high C = 24.8\n|Jul high C = 28.4\n|Aug high C = 27.8\n|Sep high C = 23.4\n|Oct high C = 18.5\n|Nov high C = 12.8\n|Dec high C = 8.6\n|year high C = 17.9\n|Jan mean C = 1.5\n|Feb mean C = 2.8\n|Mar mean C = 5.9\n|Apr mean C = 8.3\n|May mean C = 12.6\n|Jun mean C = 16.5\n|Jul mean C = 19.4\n|Aug mean C = 18.9\n|Sep mean C = 15\n|Oct mean C = 10.9\n|Nov mean C = 5.9\n|Dec mean C = 2\n|year mean C = 10\n|Jan low C = -5.7\n|Feb low C = -5.1\n|Mar low C = -2.1\n|Apr low C = 0.7\n|May low C = 4.8\n|Jun low C = 8.1\n|Jul low C = 10.3\n|Aug low C = 9.9\n|Sep low C = 6.6\n|Oct low C = 3.4\n|Nov low C = -1.1\n|Dec low C = -4.5\n|year low C = 2.1\n|Jan record low C = -20.5\n|Feb record low C = -18.8\n|Mar record low C = -19.0\n|Apr record low C = -9\n|May record low C = -4\n|Jun record low C = -0.8\n|Jul record low C = 2.5\n|Aug record low C = 1\n|Sep record low C = -2.2\n|Oct record low C = -9\n|Nov record low C = -15.5\n|Dec record low C = -19.5\n|year record low C = -20.5\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 67.1\n|Feb precipitation mm = 50.4\n|Mar precipitation mm = 51.5\n|Apr precipitation mm = 82.1\n|May precipitation mm = 92.2\n|Jun precipitation mm = 75.5\n|Jul precipitation mm = 42.4\n|Aug precipitation mm = 66.9\n|Sep precipitation mm = 91.9\n|Oct precipitation mm = 117.9\n|Nov precipitation mm = 109\n|Dec precipitation mm = 89\n|year precipitation mm = 935.9\n|unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 6.1\n|Feb precipitation days = 5.5\n|Mar precipitation days = 6.1\n|Apr precipitation days = 9.3\n|May precipitation days = 9.1\n|Jun precipitation days = 7.1\n|Jul precipitation days = 4.5\n|Aug precipitation days = 5.1\n|Sep precipitation days = 6.6\n|Oct precipitation days = 8.3\n|Nov precipitation days = 7.5\n|Dec precipitation days = 7.6\n|year precipitation days = 82.7\n|date=April 2019}}\n\n=== Geology ===\n{{See also|Geology of the Alps}}\nThe commune is part of the [[Jurassic]] [[limestone]] area of the [[French Prealps]] in [[Provence]], formed by the [[tectonics|tectonic]] upheaval of the Alps during the [[Tertiary]]. [[Limestone]] deposits run the length of the Verdon river, giving rise to spectacular gorges formed through [[karst]] [[erosion]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|author=Direction r\u00e9gionale de l'environnement (DIREN) \n|title=Les gorges du Verdon [archive]\n|work=Inventaire d\u00e9partemental des sites class\u00e9s\n|publisher=DIREN|date=October 2003\n|id= Accessed 24 August 2012\n}}</ref> Around Castellane older formations surface, such as [[gypsum]] and [[Triassic]] black [[marl]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Atlas des paysages des Alpes de Haute-Provence: Les Gorges du Verdon|page=443 |url=http://www.donnees.paca.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/docHTML/atlas04/files/4de/4de_33_fc.pdf|author=DREAL PACA, Direction R\u00e9gionale de 'Environnement, de'Am\u00e9nagement et du Logement, Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur|publisher=Pr\u00e9fet de la r\u00e9gion Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur|format=PDF|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 2008|title=Les gorges du Verdon: Contexte reglementaire|author=Direction r\u00e9gionale de l'environnement (DIREN PACA)|work=catalogue d\u00e9partemental des sites class\u00e9s, Var et Alpes de Haute-Provence|url=http://www.basecommunale.paca.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/pdf/fiches/sites_classes/93C00001.pdf}}</ref>\n\n'''Neighboring mountains and passes'''\n*Castellard ({{convert|1,725|m|ft|0|abbr=on|disp=or}})\n*Pr\u00e9 Chauvin ({{convert|1,741|m|ft|0|abbr=on|disp=or}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altituderando.com/Cadieres-de-Brandis-par-le-sommet|title=Cadi\u00e8res de Brandis par le sommet du Pr\u00e9 Chauvin (1741m)|language=French}}</ref>\n*{{Interlanguage link multi|L\u00e8ques Pass|fr|3=Col des L\u00e8ques}}, the route taken by [[Napoleon]]\n*Blaches Pass, on the road to [[Saint-Andr\u00e9-les-Alpes]]\n\n=== Environment ===\n[[File:Lac_de_castillon_la_colle.jpg|thumb|right|Lac de Castillon]]\nThe commune contains {{convert|7000|acres|abbr=off}} of wood and forests (about 59% of its surface area).<ref>\n{{Cite web\n|url=http://tresordesregions.mgm.fr/Mdir.php?p=cant.php&cl=Castellane&region=93\n|title=France, le tr\u00e9sor des r\u00e9gions\n|website=tresordesregions.mgm.fr\n|access-date=2016-04-27\n}}</ref> The {{Interlanguage link multi|Massif du Montdenier|fr}} extends over the western part of the commune (former communes of Taulanne, Chasteuil and Villars-Brandis).\n\n=== History of place names ===\n{{See also|Toponym}}\n[[File:Castellane_-_Petra_Castellana_-2.jpg|thumb|left|Petra Castellana]]\nCastellane's name appeared in texts for the first time circa 965\u2013977 as ''Petra Castellana''. The name breaks down into three [[Occitan]] terms, ''p\u00e8ira'', ''castel'' and the suffix ''-ana,'' which means fortified rock and village, and could be translated as \"Castellane rock\", in other words, the rock that has a fortified village,<ref name=EN>\n{{cite book\n|author=Ernest N\u00e8gre\n|title=Toponymie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la France: \u00e9tymologie de 35 000 noms de lieux, vol. 3 : Formations dialectales (suite); formations fran\u00e7aises\n|location=Geneva\n|publisher=Librairie Droz\n|work=Publications romanes et fran\u00e7aises\n|issue=195\n|year=1991\n|via=Google Books\n|isbn=2600028846\n}}|\u00a7 26663, pages=1465-1466\n</ref> or simply the stronghouse or stronghold. Castellane is called ''Castelana'' in the [[Proven\u00e7al dialect]] in the classical norm, or ''Castelano'' in the [[Mistralian norm|Mistralian]].\n[[File:Chasteuil-v.jpg|thumb|right|Village of Chasteuil]]\nThe former commune of Castillon, now beneath the lake, appeared around 1300 as ''de Castilhone'', an [[Occitan language|Occitan]] word for a small castle.<ref>\n{{cite book\n|author1=B\u00e9n\u00e9dicte F\u00e9ni\u00e9\n|author2=Jean-Jacques F\u00e9ni\u00e9\n|title=Toponymie proven\u00e7ale\n|publisher=\u00c9ditions Sud-Ouest\n|year=2002\n|isbn=978-2-87901-442-5\n| page=65\n}}</ref><ref>N\u00e8gre, op. cit., volume 3, \u00a7 26720, p 1470</ref>\n\nThe first part of the name \"Chasteuil\" is obscure, but the second, ''-ialo'', is a Celtic suffix for \"clearing\".<ref>F\u00e9ni\u00e9 & F\u00e9ni\u00e9, op. cit., p. 41</ref>\n\n[[File:Robion_calade.jpg|thumb|left|Robion]]\n\nThe village of ''Robion'' has the same name as the river that and flows through it  into the {{Interlanguage link multi|Jabron River|fr|3=Jabron_(affluent_du_Verdon)}} and takes its source from the Massif du Robion to the east of the village. The name ''in Rubione'', which first appeared for it in 1045, is derived from the vulgar Latin ''robigonem'', a distortion of the classical Latin ''robiginem'' for rust, according to [[Ernest N\u00e8gre]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ernest N\u00e8gre|title= Toponymie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la France: \u00e9tymologie de 35 000 noms de lieux, vol. 1: Formations pr\u00e9celtiques, celtiques, romanes |location=Geneva |publisher=Librairie Droz |work=Publications romanes et fran\u00e7aises |issue=193 |year=1990 |isbn=978-2-600-02884-4 |page=306|language=French|trans-title=General Toponymy of France: Etymology of 35,000 Place Names, vol.1: Celtic, Pre-Celtic and Roman Constructions}} \u00a7 5142</ref> [[Charles Rostaing]], on the other hand, believed that the name might predate the Gauls and designate a steep-sided ravine.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n{{Interlanguage link multi|Taloire|fr}}, was first mentioned in 1095 when the ch\u00e2teau of Taloire was given to the [[Abbey of St. Victor, Marseille]], which became the lay ''seigneur'' of the fief. It derived its name from the Occitan ''[[:fr:wikt:talador#Occitan|talador]]'', meaning soldiers especially recruited to devastate the land of an adversary. Adding the -ia suffix designates, either a land inhabited by these devastators, or a land devastated by the ''taladors''. Rostaing thought this name also probably also predated the Gauls. {{Interlanguage link multi|B\u00e9n\u00e9dicte and Jean-Jacques F\u00e9ni\u00e9|fr|3= F\u00e9ni\u00e9}} noted a [[tautology (grammar)|tautology]]: *Tal- et *Tor-, the ''teo'' roots. The name \"Taloire\" contains two terms designating a mountain.\n\n== Economy ==\nIn 2009, the unemployment rate of the Castellane population was 12.4%,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.insee.fr/fr/bases-de-donnees/?page=statistiques-locales.htm|title=Insee \u2013 Bases de donn\u00e9es \u2013 Donn\u00e9es locales|website=www.insee.fr|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> and there were 45 businesses in the secondary sector, with 84 paid workers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Prehistory and antiquity==\nThe inhabitants of Castellane are known back to a very early date. [[Neolithic]] [[nomad]]s came through the area; the oldest traces date back to 6000 BC. A grotto with [[cave painting]]s exists in the commune but its location is kept confidential to protect the artwork;<ref>{{cite book|author=Jean Gagnepain|title=Pr\u00e9histoire du Verdon, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence et Var: des origines \u00e0 la conqu\u00eate romaine |publisher=\u00c9disud |location=Aix-en-Provence|year=2002 |isbn=2-7449-0347-7 |language=fr| via=French Wikipedia, preface by Jean Courtin | page=75}}</ref> [[Bronze Age]] tombs have also been discovered in a cave in Castillon. [[Ligures|Ligurian]] tribes occupied the territory. The Suetrii or Su\u00e8tres later created an ''[[oppidum]]''{{efn|from the Latin \"oppidum\" (fortified camp on a hill).}}  named ''Ducelia'', near the Roc. They mined salt in the area and sold it. Most of the communes attached to Castellane today were peopled by the Suetrii.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/sracf_1159-7151_2004_act_25_1_1194|title= Castellane / Salinae (Alpes-de-Haute-Provence) |author=Guy Barruol|work=Capitales \u00e9ph\u00e9m\u00e8res. Des Capitales de cit\u00e9s perdent leur statut dans l'Antiquit\u00e9 tardive, Actes du colloque Tours 6\u20138 mars 2003{{!}} Supplement |publisher=Revue arch\u00e9ologique du centre de la France |year=2004|volume=25|number=1|pages=393\u2013395|language=French}}</ref> Taulanne was the exception, inhabited by the people who had their capital in [[Senez]]. (Their name is uncertain and Roman historians differ on the subject.<ref>See Guy Barruol, \u00ab Senez dans l'Antiquit\u00e9 \u00bb, in Juliette Hermellin, Senez en Haute-Provence, p. 15\u201317 and very long discussion of the topic at [https://books.google.com/books?id=kFFBAAAAcAAJ Charles G. de Bochat], ''M\u00e9moires Critiques, Pour servir d'Eclaircissements sur divers Points de L'Histoire Ancienne De La Suisse Et Sur Les Monumens D'Antiquit\u00e9 Qui la concernent''. Volume 1. Bousquet 1747, page 42.</ref>)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Brigitte Beaujard|title=Les cit\u00e9s de la Gaule m\u00e9ridionale du IIIe au VIIe si\u00e8cle|work=Gallia|issue=63|year=2006|publisher=CNRS \u00e9ditions| page=22}}</ref>\n[[File:CILXII,5437milliaireCastellane.jpg|thumb|right|Roman milestone]]\nThe region was conquered by [[Augustus]] in 14 BC. Castellane was attached to the Roman province of [[Alpes-Maritimes]] and began to grow. Homes were established in the plain, and the city was named ''Civitas Saliniensum'' (city of salt merchants). The name of the town later became Salinae.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BV1iAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA301|via=Google Books, British Library|title=The Classical Gazetteer: a Dictionary of Ancient Geography, Sacred and Profane|page=301|year=1851|language=English|author=William Hazlitt}}</ref>\n\nSeveral roads left from or passed through the town:\n* Via Salinaria, going west towards [[Durance]] and the current [[Ch\u00e2teau-Arnoux]] \n* Via Ventiana, from [[Cimiez]] to [[Sisteron]] by way of [[Vence]];<ref>{{cite news |title=A la rencontre du patrimoine : d\u00e9couverte de la carri\u00e8re Romaine: \u00c0 la recherche des milliaires oubli\u00e9s... au Col de Vence |work= Vence, cit\u00e9 d'Art et d'Azur |publisher= Ville de Vence |year=2016 |author= Marc Chaix}}</ref> a carved [[milestone]] from the beginning of the third century was found on this road in the Saint-Pierre pass<ref>{{cite book|title=La France: Collection des guides Joanne \u2013 guides diamant| author=Adolphe Joanne|edition=2|editor=Librairie Hachette et Cie |date=1873 |via=Google Books, Biblioth\u00e8que de Catalogne|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cwkapexu8XIC&pg=PR1}}</ref> six miles from Castellane\n* a fork towards [[Via Aurelia]] and Via [[Domitia]]\n* a road towards [[Entrevaux]] ([[Gland\u00e8ves]]) by way of [[Brian\u00e7onnet]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archeam.fr/sites/www.archeam.fr/files/pdf/archeam7/archeam_7_chavane_voie_romaine_castellane_brianconnet_entrevaux.pdf|title=Description d'une voie romaine reliant Castellane a Brian\u00e7onnet et Entrevaux (Gland\u00e8ves)&#124;Vincent Chavanne|work=Arch\u00e9ologia|date=November 1995|language=French|trans-title=Description of a Roman Road Linking Castellane to Brian\u00e7onnet and Entrevaux (Gland\u00e8ves)}}</ref>\n\nResidents first settled on the bank of the Verdon to mine the saline sources which are still visible today. A treasure of antiquity, 34 gold coins issued by [[Arcadius]] and [[Honorius (emperor)|Honorius]], were discovered in 1797 in Taloire. A limestone funerary stele for one Julius Trofimus, dating back to Roman times, was discovered near the old chapel of Notre-Dame-du-Plan. Until 1942 it was used in a retaining wall, and can be found today in the public garden of the savings bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000058 |title=Mobilier |year=1992 |work=Palissy database|publisher=minist\u00e8re fran\u00e7ais de la Culture}}</ref> The inscription is included in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Inscriptions latines de Gaule narbonnaise|fr}} (ILGN) collection of [[Gallia Narbonensis]] Roman inscriptions and is listed on the historic register.\n\nA diocese was founded in the fifth century: its seat was transferred to Senez before the 6th century however and despite all attempts to have it return to Castellan it remained there until it was closed in the French Revolution.\n\n==Middle Ages==\n[[File:Castellane_Notre_Dame_du_Roc2.jpg|thumb|left]]\nIn the early ninth century, the area around the current town of Castellane was inhabited by only 84 people. In 812 the area was invaded by Moors, also sometimes called Saracens; they destroyed ''Salines'', the early settlement near the salt marshes.<ref name=gros>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7flPwL6Da9sC |title=Antiquit\u00e9s de l'arrondissement de Castellanne |edition=2 |via=University of Oxford, Google Books |year=1842 |author= Gras-Bourguet |publisher= Digne |language=French}}</ref> The inhabitants of Salines took refuge on the summit of the Roc and built a stronghold there, building the first Notre-Dame there, inaugurated in 852, in thanks for the refuge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basecommunale.paca.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/pdf/fiches/sites_classes/93C04004.pdf |title=CASTELLANE: LE ROC NOTRE-DAME |author=DIREN PACA |work=catalogue d\u00e9partemental des sites class\u00e9s, Alpes de Haute-Provence|year=2003}}</ref> Some vestiges of this site, which was named ''Sinaca'' in 813 and ''Petra Castellana'' in 965, are still visible at the place now known as ''Le Signal''. People later also settled at the foot of the Roc in the valley bottom.\n\nIn 852 a lord of Castellane, possibly named Guillaume<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EVk_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA115|via=Bibliotheque cant. et univ. Lausanne, Google Books|page=115|title=Dictionnaire g\u00e9ographique, historique et politique des Gaules et de la France|author=Jean-Joseph Expilly|year=1764|publisher=Desaint & Saillant|trans-title=Geographical, Historical and Political Dictionary of the Gauls and of France}}</ref> won a victory against the Moors and put together a barony of 46 village communities stretching from [[Cotignac]] in [[Var (department)|Var]] to the south, to [[Thorame-Haute]] in the north, and from [[Soleilhas]] to [[Esparron-de-Verdon]]. The Barony was considered a small sovereign state ruled by hereditary sovereign barons.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=baron+de+Castellane+,+comme+souverain+ind%C3%A9pendant&sig=ACfU3U3JplJUKAJgmLDXy3ybyToTqdoW1w&id=rGI_AQAAMAAJ&ots=sqzxUrQcTr&output=text|title=Annuaire de la noblesse de France|date=1894|publisher=Au Bureau de la publication|language=fr}}</ref> <!-- from french wikipedia, <s>still needs a reference --> Over time Castellane came to have three co-existing sites:\n*the Rupes, on top of the Rock, was soon entirely occupied by the castle built in 977 by Pons-Arbaud and [[Aldebert]]<!-- date problem, alive much earlier (?) -->\n*the Castrum, halfway up, on a larger site but easy to defend;\n*the Burgum, current site of Castellane, easily accessible, facilitating trade.<ref name=HB>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rfNpxIJUikQC&pg=PA276|page=913|title=La chorographie ou description de Prouence et l'histoire chronologique du mesme pays. Tome premier (-second). Par le sieur Honor\u00e9 Bouch\u00e9|via=Carmelitani: Biblioteca Torino, Google Books|year=1664|language=French}}</ref>\n[[File:Ch\u00e2teau_de_Rougon_3.JPG|thumb|right|Ruined ch\u00e2teau in Rougon]]\nIn 1189, Baron de Castellane Boniface III was attacked by [[Alfonso II of Aragon|Alfonso I of Provence]]. He had refused to do homage, explaining that he was a vassal of the Holy Roman Empire. But in the face of brute force he was forced to bend the knee. Another war broke out in 1227 between the Provence and Boniface of Castellane, presumably the son.<ref>{{cite book |title= La chorographie ou description de Prouence et l'histoire chronologique du mesme pays. Tome premier (-second). Par le sieur Honor\u00e9 Bouch\u00e9 |author= Honor\u00e9 Bouch\u00e9  |date=1664 |via= Google Books, University of Turin (Carmelitani: Biblioteca Torino) |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=rfNpxIJUikQC&pg=PP7 |page= 919}}</ref> In 1257 Charles II\u2014then still just prince of Salernes, gave the castle to the Austinian monks. In 1262, [[Charles I of Naples|Charles I of Anjou]] defeated [[Bonifaci VI de Castellana|Boniface of Castellane]] and made Castelle the seat of a [[:fr:wikt:baile#Ancien occitan|baile]]. In the thirteenth century, the family of Castellane lost possession of the city to the Counts of Provence. To protect themselves from attack, in addition to the protections for the city, Castellane built a series of fortified outposts at [[Demandolx]], [[La Garde, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|La Garde]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Chasteuil|fr}}, [[Rougon]], and perhaps Taloire.{{when|date=September 2016}} In 1300 a small Jewish community of eight households was established in the area.<ref>{{cite book|author=\u00c9douard Baratier|title=La d\u00e9mographie proven\u00e7ale du XIIIe au XVIe si\u00e8cles, avec chiffres de comparaison pour le XVIIIe si\u00e8cle|location=Paris|publisher=SEVPEN/EHESS|year=1961|work=Collection D\u00e9mographie et soci\u00e9t\u00e9|number=5| page=70|language=French|trans-title=Proven\u00e7al Demography in from the 13th to the 16th century, with numbers compared to the 18th century}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Black Death]] reached Castellane in 1348, and was followed by a devastating flood of the [[Verdon River]]. The capture and death of Queen [[Joanna I of Naples]] created a succession issue in the county of Provence, the cities of the [[Union of Aix]] (1382\u20131387) supporting [[Charles III of Naples|Charles de Duras]] against [[Louis I, Duke of Anjou|Louis I of Anjou]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n|title=Volume 1 of Inventaire sommaire des archives communales ant\u00e9rieures \u00e0 1790\n|work=Inventaire sommaire des archives communales ant\u00e9rieures \u00e0 1790\n|author=Ministry of the Interior, France\n|publisher=Imprimerie E. Aurel\n|year=1866\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7sNEAQAAMAAJ\n|via=Google Books and University of Chicago\n|page=393\n}}\n</ref>\n[[File:Castellane_-_Ch\u00e2teau_d'\u00c9oulx_-3.JPG|thumb|left|Ch\u00e2teau_d'\u00c9oulx]]\nLord of Castellane Louis d'Anduse, also often known<ref>{{cite book|page=16|title=Annales de Haute Provence| language=French |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yXI2AAAAMAAJ |author=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 scientifique et litt\u00e9raire des Basses-Alpes |location=Digne|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 scientifique et litt\u00e9raire des Alpes-de-haute-provence |year=1894 |via=University of Michigan, Google Books|volume=6}}</ref> as Lord of La Voulte,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2gU9AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA169|title=Nobiliaire universel de France: ou Recueil g\u00e9n\u00e9ral des g\u00e9n\u00e9alogies historiques des maisons nobles de ce royaume, Volume 3 |language=French|page=169|via=Google Books, University of California|author1=M. de Saint-Allais (Nicolas Viton)|author2=Ange Jacques Marie Poisson de La Chabeaussi\u00e8re |author3=Jean Baptiste Pierre Jullien de Courcelles|author4=Lespines (abb\u00e9 de), Ducas Johann Lanz|publisher=bureau du Nobiliaire universel de France, R\u00e9imprim\u00e9 \u00e0 la Librairie Bachelin-Deflorenne |year=1873}}</ref> sided with the [[Louis I, Duke of Anjou|Duke of Anjou]] from the spring of 1382, supporting him on condition he participate in an expedition to rescue the queen.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Genevi\u00e8ve Xhayet|title=Partisans et adversaires de Louis d'Anjou pendant la guerre de l'Union d'Aix|work=Provence historique|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration historique de Provence|volume=40|issue=162, \"Autour de la guerre de l'Union d'Aix\"|year=1990|pages=417\u2013419}}</ref> Castellane itself initially also backed the Duke, but changed allegiance in February 1386 after the Duke died, and rallied to the cause of the queen-regent, [[Marie of Blois, Duchess of Anjou|Marie de Blois]]. She negotiated with them, hoping to set off a chain of similar declarations of support. Guillaume de Forcalquier and his son Jean Raynaut, lords of Eoulx, submitted to the Duchess in July 1386. In 1390, {{Interlanguage link multi|Raymond de Turenne|fr|3=Raimond de Turenne}} ravaged the surrounding territory and the village of Taulanne and failed to take the city, but did destroy the wooden bridge over the Verdon River.\n[[File:Castellane_-180.jpg|thumb|right|Pont du Roc]]\nThe wooden bridge over the Verdon was rebuilt in stone in the 15th century. A [[Bridge-Building Brotherhood|monastery]] took care of its maintenance.<ref>{{cite book|author=Baratier, Duby & Hildesheimer|title=Les \u00e9tablissements des ordres militaires et hospitaliers en Provence (XIIIe-XIVe si\u00e8cles)| page=map 68}}</ref> The bridge on the Place Castellane put Castellane on the frequently travelled routes between the  Mediterranean and the bridge over the [[Durance]] river at [[Sisteron]]. The bridge toll for the Verdon and the fair began at the end of the Middle Ages. The fair continued until the end of the ''[[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]'', assuring the town relative prosperity.\n\nIn the fifteenth century, a community settled on the present site of Taloire. In the middle of the fifteenth century, the upper village was completely abandoned in favor of the lowland site.\n\n==Renaissance==\n[[File:Draille.JPG|thumb|right|Draille in Robion]]\nAt the end of the Middle Ages, the [[transhumance]] system developed enormously, herds of sheep from the coast going up into the high Alpine valleys in the summer. Some ''[[drover's road|drailles]]'' (herding routes) crossed the Castellane bridge, where a toll was instituted. At the beginning of the 16th century, between 78,000 and 120,000 head were crossing each year during May and June.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pierre Coste|author2=No\u00ebl Coulet|title=Que sait-on des origines de la transhumance en Provence?|editor1=Jean-Claude Duclos|editor2=Andr\u00e9 Pitte|work=L'homme et le mouton dans l'espace de la transhumance (Man and Sheep in Transhumance)|location=Grenoble|publisher=Gl\u00e9nat|year=1994|isbn=2-7234-1746-8| page=68|trans-title=What is known of the origin of transhumance in Provence?|language=French}}</ref>\n[[File:Jakob_Seisenegger_001.jpg|thumb|left|Charles V]]\nThe imperial army of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] pillaged the town en 1536.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michel de La Torre|title=Alpes-de-Haute-Provence: le guide complet des 200 communes|trans-title=Alpes-de-Haute-Provence: Complete Guide to the 200 communes|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=Deslogis-Lacoste|work=collection \"Villes et villages de France\"|year=1989|isbn=2-7399-5004-7}}</ref>\n\nReligious unrest broke out in 1559. Brun de Caille had converted some of the townspeople of Castellane, who gathered at his home for services. A sectarian skirmish took place at his home.<ref name=gros/> [[Huguenot]] captain {{Interlanguage link multi|Paulon de Mauvans|fr}}, of another rich Protestant family, sacked the town in the summer of 1560,<ref>{{cite book|author=Pierre Miquel |title=Les Guerres de Religion |trans-title=The Wars of Religion|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=Club France Loisirs|year=1980|isbn=2-7242-0785-8| page=211}}</ref> then established himself there after reaching an armistice with the governor of Provence, the count of [[Tende]], [[Claude of Savoy]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} <!-- based on dates in wikipedia articles --> The town was attacked by Protestants on 4 October 1574, but the residents of Castellane and its surroundings chased them off, pursuing them as far as the ''clue de Taulanne''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jacques Cru|title=Histoire des Gorges du Verdon jusqu'\u00e0 la R\u00e9volution|trans-title=History of the Gorges of the Verdon| page=200}}</ref>\nOn 30 January 1586, the {{Interlanguage link multi|Baron of Allemagne|fr|3=Nicolas_Mas-Castellane}} and the [[Fran\u00e7ois de Bonne, Duke of Lesdigui\u00e8res|Duke of Lesdigui\u00e8res]] tried to surprise the town. The sneak attack was repulsed and the Baron d'Allemagne was injured by a bullet in his back, which caused the assailants to retreat. The Baron was killed in September of that year trying to lift the siege of his own castle, shot in the head by an [[arquebus]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=XVe journ\u00e9e arch\u00e9ologique|work=Annales de Haute-Provence|volume=308 2e trimestre|year=1989| pages=17\u201318}}</ref>\nThe end of the siege of Castellane has since been celebrated every year in the last weekend of January with the ''P\u00e9tardiers'' ceremony reenacting the attack, and notably the episode of Judith Andr\u00e9 or Andrau, the goodwife of [[Barr\u00eame]],<ref>{{cite book|author=J.-F. Cruvellier|title=Histoire de Barr\u00eame|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 scientifique et litt\u00e9raire des Basses-Alpes| page=4}}</ref> who killed ''p\u00e9tardier'' captain Jean Motte by pouring a kettle of boiling peas over him from the top of the ''porte de l'Annonciade'', reputed to be the weak point in the defenses.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jacques Cru|title=Histoire des Gorges du Verdon jusqu'\u00e0 la R\u00e9volution| page=203}}</ref>\ns1z\n\n==17th and 18th century==\nThe [[plague (disease)|plague]] struck the town again in 1630.\n\nThe [[Jansenist]] bishop [[Jean Soanen]] tried to make the celebrations of [[Corpus Christi (feast)|Saint-Sacrement]], [[Nativity of St John the Baptist|Saint-Jean]] and [[Saint Eligius|Saint-\u00c9loi]] more sedate and less unbridled, the youth of the town having a tradition of celebrating with drums, music and gunshots. The youth refused, resisted, made even more noise and even revolted, preventing the procession of the octave du Saint-Sacrement from leaving the church on June 22, 1710.<ref name=nic>{{cite book|author=Jean Nicolas|title=La R\u00e9bellion fran\u00e7aise: mouvements populaires et conscience sociale, 1661\u20131789 |language=French|trans-title=The French Rebellion: Popular Movements and Social Conscience |location=Paris |publisher= Gallimard |year=2008 |series= Collection Folio |isbn= 978-2-07-035971-4 | page=703}}</ref> In 1726 the youth of Robion, whom the priest wanted to prevent from dancing on Sunday, also revolted.<ref name=nic/>\n[[File:Castellane,_D4085,_clue_de_Taulanne,_du_sud.jpg|thumb|left|Clue de Taulanne]]\nThe Austrian-Sardinian army briefly occupied the town in 1746 during the [[war of the Austrian Succession]]. In December 1746, Provence was invaded by an Austrian-Sardinian army. A troop of 2,000 men took Castellane,<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pierre Grillon|title=L'invasion et la lib\u00e9ration de la Provence en 1746\u20131747|work=Provence historique|volume=12|issue=50|year=1962|page=345|language=French|trans-title=The invasion and liberation of Provence in 1746\u20131747}}</ref> then the surrounding villages, as far as the ch\u00e2teau of [[Trigance]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pierre Grillon|title=L'invasion et la lib\u00e9ration de la Provence en 1746\u20131747|work=Provence historique|volume=12|issue=50|year=1962|page=353|language=French|trans-title=The invasion and liberation of Provence in 1746\u20131747}}</ref> After some difficulty, the Spanish and French armies coordinated a counteroffensive, which began at the start of January when French soldiers under the orders of the [[Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing|Count of Maul\u00e9vrier]] took an Austrian outpost in Chasteuil.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pierre Grillon|title=L'invasion et la lib\u00e9ration de la Provence en 1746\u20131747|work=Provence historique|volume=12|issue=50|year=1962|page=352|language=French|trans-title=The invasion and liberation of Provence in 1746\u20131747}}</ref> The Austrian commander, [[Maximilian Ulysses Browne]], reinforced his right wing with four battalions garrisoned at Castellane, and six on the south bank of the Verdon. Seven other battalions formed a second available squadron. Nine battalions and ten squads of Spaniards were stationed in [[Riez]] and 2,500 Swiss paid by Spain were stationed at Senez. The 21st of January, Hispano-French troops went on the offensive, commanded by the Frenchman Maul\u00e9vrier and the Spanish Marquis of Taubin.<ref>\n{{cite book\n|title=The History of the War of MDCCXLI.: Containing the History of that War Till the Peace of Aix-la-Chapelle in 1748. In Three Parts. By M. de Voltaire. To which is Annexed, a Particular Account of the Rise, Progress, and Extinction of the Rebellion in G. Britain in 1745 and 1746\n|editor=W. Gray\n|year=1758\n|via=British Library, Google Books\n|page=258\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EZDY2ky-WmsC&pg=PA258\n}}\n</ref> The Spanish left their quarters by night and advanced on Castellane through the ''clue de Taulanne'', while the French passing through the Vodon gorge. The difficult marches necessary to approach in this way nonetheless allowed a coordinated attack around 7am.\n\nThe first outposts were taken without difficulty, which allowed Maul\u00e9vrier to connect on his left with Taubin, and to send a column of [[dragoons]] onto the right bank to cut the Austrians' retreat. This assault took the Austrian-Sardinians fortifications without difficulty, the French-Spanish entered the town and did prevent the last Austrians from retreating. In all, they took 287 Austrians prisoner, including the baron de Neuhaus,<ref>{{cite book|page=173|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DTZbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA173|title=Lettres historiques: contenant ce qui se passe de plus important en Europe et les r\u00e9flexions n\u00e9cessaires sur ce sujet..., Volume 122|author1=Jacques Bernard|author2=Henri Basnage (sieur de Beauval)|author3=Jean du Mont |editor=Adrian Moetjens|year=1747|language=French|via=Google Books, Universit\u00e9 de Gand}}</ref> the lieutenant-general in command. The Austrian-Sardinians also had a hundred-odd dead, versus twenty Franco-Spanish soldiers. The villages of La Garde, Eoulx, Robion, Taloire, Trigance and Comps were evacuated on January 22.\n[[File:FR_Var_Trigance_old_street.JPG|thumb|right|Street in Trigance]]\nIn 1760, a tax imposed by the king of Piedmont-Sardinia on sales of cloth brought a large reduction in the town's textile production. Production of {{Interlanguage link multi|cadis|fr}}, a local form of wool, and of ''cordeillat'', a coarse woolen fabric, continued until the Revolution, and was used by the local residents.\n\nUntil the Revolution salt was produced from two local salt marshes.\n\nOn the eve of the [[French Revolution]], several [[fiefs]] existed on the actual territory of the commune: \u00c9oulx, Le Castellet-de-Robion (which became a [[feudal barony|barony]] in 1755), Chasteuil, Taulanne and Castillon, plus Castellane. On the same territory there were nine [[parish]]es: Castillon, La Baume, Taulanne, La Palud, Chasteuil, Taloire, Villars-Brandis, Robion, et Castellane. The parish of \u00c9oulx overlapped the community of La Garde.\n\nThe city of Castellane alone paid more tax than [[Digne]]; it was an important rural town, both for its judiciary functions (with eight lawyers and five prosecutors) and for its production, with twelve factories: among which were six hat shops, two wax factories, one fa\u00efence works, one tile factory, one silk fabrication works, and the leather industry was also represented.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pr\u00e9fecture des Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|title=Histoire de la Sous-Pr\u00e9fecture de Castellane|publisher=Pr\u00e9fecture des Alpes de Haute-Provence}}</ref> A royal post office was also installed in Castellane near the end of the ''[[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=\u00c9mile Lauga|title=La poste dans les Basses-Alpes, ou l'histoire du courrier de l'Antiquit\u00e9 \u00e0 l'aube du XXe si\u00e8cle|language=French|trans-title=Postal Service in the Basses-Alpes, or the History of Mail from Antiquity to the Dawn of the 20th Century|location=Digne-les-Bains|publisher=\u00c9ditions de Haute-Provence|year=1994|isbn=2-909800-64-4| page=58}}</ref>\n\n==19th century==\n[[File:Le_Commerce...Quand_donc..._LACMA_M.91.82.251.jpg|thumb|left|Political cartoon in ''Le Charivari'', 2 December 1851. The caption says \"When are you going to stop playing these games? I am getting tired of paying for them.\"]]\nThe cloth industry, already well established in the preceding century, prospered in the first half of the 19th century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Raymond Collier|title=La Haute-Provence monumentale et artistique|location=Digne|publisher=Imprimerie Louis Jean|year=1986|page=414}}</ref> But cottage industries were replaced by the Barneaud factory, built in the late 1830s on the model of the Honnorat factory in [[Saint-Andr\u00e9-les-Alpes|Saint-Andr\u00e9-de-M\u00e9ouilles]]. It employed nine workers in 1872, then disappeared in 1878.<ref>{{cite thesis|author=Mireille Mistral\n|title=L'industrie drapi\u00e8re dans la all\u00e9e du Verdon |type=doctoral |publisher=Acad\u00e9mie d'Aix-en-Provence|location=Nice|year=1951|page=41}}</ref>\n\nThe Revolution and the Empire brought social reforms, including proportional taxation based on the assets. In order to put this in place on a precise basis, a land registry was drawn up. The ''loi de finances du 15 septembre 1807'' specified its methods, but its accomplishment took time to get started, since the officials conducting the ''[[cadastre]]'' dealt with the ''communes'' in successive geographic groups. Not until 1834\u20131835 was the land registry known as the Napoleonic cadastre of Castellane and its associated communes finished.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Alexe\u00ef Laurent|title=Paysages ruraux de la premi\u00e8re moiti\u00e9 du XIXe si\u00e8cle dans le sud-est des Basses-Alpes|editor=Jean-Christophe Labadie|series=''La mati\u00e8re et le b\u00e2ti en Haute-Provence, XVIIIe-XXIe si\u00e8cle'', proceedings of the first History of Haute-Provence Day (Journ\u00e9e d'\u00e9tudes d'histoire de la Haute-Provence), Digne, 13 October 2012|work=Digne-les-Bains: Archives d\u00e9partementales des Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|year=2013|isbn=978-2-86004-016-7| page=10}}</ref>\n\nThe [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] of 2 December 1851 committed by Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte against the [[French Second Republic|Second Republic]] provoked an armed uprising in the [[Basses-Alpes]] in defense of the Constitution. Insurgent republicans took a number of cities in the center and south of France, including [[Digne]], the prefecture of the [[Basses-Alpes]], and held them for several days. The local fighters held out the longest, almost three weeks. But this allowed Bonaparte to portray himself as the protector of France, and many participants were sent to penal colonies in [[Lambesa]] and [[Cayenne]], banished or less permanently exiled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cairn.info/revue-parlements1-2009-2-page-24.htm#no34|title=Le coup d\u2019\u00c9tat du 2 d\u00e9cembre 1851 ou la chronique de deux morts annonc\u00e9es et l\u2019av\u00e8nement d\u2019un grand principe|author=Eric Anceau|work=Parlement[s], Revue d'histoire politique |year=2009 |volume=12 |publisher=L'Harmattan|issn=1760-6233 |language=French}}</ref> Eight inhabitants of Castellane were brought before the ''commission mixte''; their most common penalty was deportation to Algeria.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Henri Joannet|author2=Jean-Pierre Pinatel|title=Arrestations-condamnations 1851|trans-title=Arrests-Convictions 1851|work=Pour m\u00e9moire, Les M\u00e9es: Les Amis des M\u00e9es|year=2001|page=71}}</ref>\n\n==20th century==\n[[File:RN_85,_st\u00e8le_col_des_L\u00e8ques.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial to FTP fighters]]\nOn 10 September 1926, the sous-pr\u00e9fecture was eliminated in the economic plan of [[Raymond Poincar\u00e9]], then re-established by the [[Vichy government]] in June 1942.\n\nAn [[internment]] camp was built in Chaudanne during [[World War II]]. Seventeen Jews were arrested in Castellane and deported. On 9 December 1943, the French [[arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te]] (AS) and the [[Francs-tireurs et partisans]] (FTP) attacked the construction site at the Castillon dam and seized five tonnes of explosives.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Jean Garcin|title=La r\u00e9sistance arm\u00e9e|work=Basses-Alpes|volume=39\u201345|issue=7|date=July 2004| page=4|language=French|trans-title=Armed Resistance}}</ref>\n\nThe ''commune'' was liberated 18 August 1944 by the [[36th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|36th division]] of British infantry.\n\nIn the mid-20th century [[viticulture|wine growing]] for local consumption ended.\n\n==Sites and monuments==\n[[File:Castellane_-176.jpg|thumb|right|The Roc and the bridge of the Roc]]\nThe Rock which dominates the city, rising to {{convert|930|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} (over {{convert|200|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} above the Verdon), is a listed historical  site.\n\nThe oldest monument in the territory of the commune is the [[dolmen]] of Pierres Blanches<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00132925|title=Architecture|date=April 16, 1996|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise}}</ref> Neolithic-Chalcolithic,  a registered historical site on private property. The Roc towers {{convert|184|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} above the community of Castellane.\n\nThe Mus\u00e9e des sir\u00e8nes et fossiles and the Moyen Verdon is networked with other museums in the Gorges du Verdon, including the home of Pauline Gr\u00e9oux-les-Bains, the museum of the life of yesteryear Esparron-de-Verdon, home gorges du Verdon in La Palud-sur-Verdon and the Museum of prehistory in Quinson gorges du Verdon.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Antibes Castellane.JPG|thumb|right|In the city of Castellane]]\n\nThe bridge of the Roc, which carries the [[Sisteron]]-[[Vence]] road across the river, was built in the first decade of the fifteenth century, replacing a succession of several wooden bridges, the last spanning the Verdon in 1300 and destroyed by {{Interlanguage link multi|Raimond de Turenne|fr}} in 1390. The construction of the new bridge parallels that of [[Nyons]] (built in 1401, {{convert|42|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long), Pont de Claix (built in 1607\u201313, {{convert|45|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long), [[Tournon-sur-Rh\u00f4ne|Tournon]] (built in the sixteenth century, {{convert|49|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long) and [[Entrechaux]] ({{convert|24.5|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} long). [[Pope Benedict XIII]] granted [[indulgence]]s to anyone who gave [[alms]] to finance its construction.<ref>{{cite book|author=Serge Montens|title=Les plus beaux ponts de France|location=Paris |publisher=Bonneton |year=2001 |isbn=2-86253-275-4 |page=15}}</ref> The [[rearguard]] of the Austrian-Sardinian army was caught there by a [[sortie]] from the [[garrison]].\n[[File:France_PACA_04_Castellane_06.jpg|thumb|left|Bridge of the Roc]]\nThe [[tympanum (architecture)|tympana]] of the Roc bridge have been restored several times. Metal [[tie rod]]s were laid in 1697\u201399. The bridge as a whole was restored in 2008 and closed to traffic. It was decommissioned in 1967 and delisted in 1982. The bridge and its approaches have been a registered historical site since 1940.\n\nThe library is in the former convent of the [[Order of the Visitation of Holy Mary|Visitation]], founded in 1644. The eighteenth-century castle at \u00c9oulx is richly decorated with plasterwork, including the first floor ceilings, the panels surrounding the doors, the rosette in the second-floor ceilings. Externally, it has two towers, with arched openings. The town hall is housed in the building that used to be the savings bank. It resembles a villa: balconies supported by large [[corbel]]s and thick [[baluster]]s, and a fa\u00e7ade adorned with a [[pediment]].\n\nCatellane's largest fountain, in the main square, features a pyramid on which is carved a compass crossed by a [[carpenter's square]], two [[chisel]]s and a [[mallet]], emblems of the [[Freemasons]]. At the top of the pyramid is a [[pedestal]] with a ball. On National Street, two doors have [[transom (architectural)|transom]]s or capitals with [[volute]]s, and one [[lintel]] is decorated with carved foliage. In the town, several buildingss, mostly dry stone, have been recorded in the inventory of topographic DRAC. One of them, in Rayaup, dates from the eighteenth century (the inscription that says 1586 is very recent).\n\n==Notre-Dame du Roc==\n[[File:Castellane_7_chapelleNDduRoc.jpg|thumb|left|Notre Dame du Roc]]\nThe Chapel of Our Lady of the Rock, dating from the High Middle Ages, dominates the city from atop the Rock and belongs to the former Convent of Mercy. But only the wall and the south fa\u00e7ade date from the twelfth century; the building was half demolished during the [[French wars of religion|wars of religion]] and rebuilt in 1590.\n\nCrumbling by 1703, the chapel was again rebuilt in the early eighteenth century and once more in 1860. A capital adorned with foliage and scrolls dates from the Renaissance.\n[[File:Castellane_7_chapelleNDduRoc2.jpg|thumb|right]]\nThe furnishings include:\n*a statue of the Virgin, in marble, possibly 16th century \n*two paintings, ''St. Charles Borromeo'' and ''St. Francis and St. Jeanne de Chantal'', on the historic register for both the paintings and their gilded frames, bearing the arms of the Bishop of Senez Ducha\u00eene and dating from the seventeenth century.\n\nIt received numerous [[votive offering]]s in the 19th and 20th centuries, including:\n[[File:Castellane_7_chapelleNDduRoc3.jpg|thumb|left|Votive offerings]]\n*traditional engraved plates (136 total);\n*bridal bouquets (21 total);\n*a painting given after a vow to Our Lady, dating from 1757, and registered;\n*a painting given after the cholera epidemic in 1835, registered;\n*a painting given by a released prisoner, dated 1875 (registered);\n*a painting given in thanks after a smallpox epidemic, dated 1870, registered;\n*a painting given by a person who escaped a shipwreck in 1896, registered.\n\n==Saint-Victor==\n[[File:\u00c9glise_Saint-Victor_-_Castellane.jpg|thumb|right|Saint Victor]]\nParts of the old parish church of Saint-Victor date from the mid-11th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00080359|title=Architecture: Eglise Saint-Victor|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French|date=June 4, 1993}}</ref> It is listed as an historical building. It was constructed in a similar manner and on the same plane as the Church of St. Andrew in the old village above the modern-day town, and was formerly the seat of a [[priory]] of the [[Abbey of St. Victor, Marseille|Abbey of St. Victor]] in Marseille.\n\nThe [[apse]] is decorated with [[Lombard band]]s, which have been described as remarkable,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/ccmed_0007-9731_1977_num_20_77_2053|title=Survivances du premier art roman en Provence &#124; Surviving Traces of Early Roman Art in Provence|author=Victor Lassalle|work=Cahiers de civilisation m\u00e9di\u00e9vale|year=1977 |volume=20 |issue=77 |page=6|via=Pers\u00e9e|language=French}}</ref> each arch carved from a single stone. Unusually for the region, it has a Roman [[nave]], with arches rebuilt in the 17th century. The base of the tower dates from 1445, but its top was rebuilt in the 18th century following damage by Protestants in 1560.\n\nThe altar dates from 1724. The choir is adorned with paintings framed in wood, and an [[Annunciation]] carved in [[relief#high relief|relief]] from gilded wood (18th century, on historical register). The wooden furniture, the stalls, the pulpit and the lectern with its hexagonal base, form an interesting 18th and 19th-century set, some of which is on the historic register. The furnishings also include an early 17th-century silver chalice with an unusual multilobed foot, also on the historic register.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000641|title=Mobilier: calice|date=July 20, 2000|work=Palissy database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Other historic churches==\n[[File:Castellane_-_Sacr\u00e9-Coeur_-1.jpg|thumb|left|Sacr\u00e9-Coeur]]\n[[File:Castellane_-_\u00c9glise_paroissiale_Saint-Pons_d'\u00c9oulx_-3.JPG|thumb|right|Saint Pons in \u00c9oulx]]\n[[File:Castellane,_\u00e9glise_Saint-Pierre_de_Taulanne,_fa\u00e7ade.jpg|thumb|right|Saint Pierre de Taulanne]]\n*The Church of the Sacred Heart, now a parish church, was built in 1868\u20131873 by Father Pougnet and dedicated to Our Lady. It was widened by side aisles in 1896. The first [[transept]] is occupied by a platform. <!-- ? dais? -translator --> The interior is [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]], with the tower built against the fa\u00e7ade. The furnishings include some registered historical items:two silver ''custodes'', cases for carrying [[communion (sacrament)|communion]] hosts; one dating from around 1650<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000642|work=Palissy database|date=July 20, 2000|title=Mobilier: ciboire-chrismatoire (custode)|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise}}</ref> and one from the 18th century, a gilded wooden 18th-century cross,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000507|title=Mobilier: croix (crucifix)|date=January 29, 1990|work=Palissy database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de culture fran\u00e7ais}}</ref> and a 16th-century silver [[chalice]]\n[[File:Castellane_-_Chapelle_Saint-Antoine_d'\u00c9oulx_-1.JPG|thumb|left|Saint Antoine of \u00c9oulx]]\n*the Chapel of St. Joseph is part of the Augustinian church rebuilt to replace the chapel of the [[Blue Penitents]]. It was partly demolished to widen the boulevard Saint-Michel\n*the 12th-century {{Interlanguage link multi|Saint Thyrse Chapel|fr|3=Chapelle Saint-Thyrse de Robion}} near Robion was restored in 1942 and declared a historical monument in 1944,<ref>{{cite web|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e|title=Inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral du patrimoine culturel |language=French |trans-title=General Inventory of the Cultural Heritage|author=Ronsseray, Dominique|date=March 26, 2010}}</ref> It is the earliest Romanesque (11th and 12th centuries) church in the region. \n*Saint-Pons in Eoulx, unchanged since its construction, not arched, has preserved the original [[cornice]]s from the middle or late twelfth century, also the thirteenth century according to the [[Direction r\u00e9gionale des affaires culturelles]] (DRAC). This building is on the historic register. It has a flat copper collection plate believed to be 17th-century\n[[File:Saint-Thyrse.JPG|thumb|right|Saint Thyrse]]\n*ruins of the Church of St. Andr\u00e9 \u2013 13th century, in ruins since the 18th century (site of Petra Castellana)\n*The 12th-century church of Notre-Dame-du-Plan, a former priory in Castellane\n*Church of St. Sebastian Chasteuil (16th century)\n*Saint-Pons \u2013 16th century, with bell dated 1436, in Robion\n*Saint-Jean in Taloire, may have been built as early as the 13th or 14th century, but the 15th century seems more likely. It was damaged by the earthquake of 1951.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archeoprovence.com/archeo/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=158%3Acastellane&catid=56&Itemid=72|date=December 19, 2010|title=Recherches historiques \u00e9glises et chapelles rurales: Castellane| author=Daniel Thiery|work=Arch\u00e9oprovence}}</ref>\n*St. Pierre in Taulanne\n*Saint-Jean-Baptiste in Villars-Brandis has an exceptional late 15th-century copper [[thurible]] (a type of [[censer]]) with bilevel windows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000060|work=Palissy database|title=Mobilier|trans-title=Furnishings|publisher=minist\u00e8re fran\u00e7ais de la culture}}</ref>\n*Chapelle Sainte-Victoire in a place called Angles: late 19th century at the earliest\n*chapels of Saint-Pons Blaron (ex-Castillon), Saint-Antoine and Notre Dame (ruined) in Eoulx, \n*St. Trophimus, built into the mountain above Petit Robion after a chapel built below was repeatedly damaged by rocks falling onto its roof,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_8=REF&VALUE_8=IA04001142|title=Architecture: chapelle Saint-Trophime|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French}}</ref> has a 17th-century silver chalice and a flat copper 16th-century collection plate, both registered historical items.  \n*St. Stephen, on high ground in Taloire \n*St. John, in Villars\n*the cemetery Notre-Dame-du-Plan includes several funeral chapels\n\n==Military architecture==\n[[File:Castellane_5_PA00080362.jpg|thumb|right|Pentagonal tower]]\nThe outline of the walls of Petra Castellana, the ancient city beneath the current one, is still visible, and in places they reach seven meters in height.<ref name=CIHAM>{{cite web|url=http://ciham.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/petra-castellana-castellane-alpes-haute-provence |title= Petra Castellana (Castellane \u2013 Alpes de Haute-Provence): Campagne de sondages arch\u00e9ologiques du 6 au 17 juin 2016|publisher=Le Centre national de la recherche scientifique|work=CIHAM}}</ref> The walls are thought to date from the 12th century, although a June 2016 archeological excavation sought to date them more precisely.<ref name=CIHAM/> Only one tower survives of the fourteen that originally reinforced these walls: the 14th-century pentagonal keep. This keep, which dominates the town center, is on private property but was declared a historic monument in 1921.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00080362|title=Architecture: Tour pentagonale du 14s sur une hauteur dominant la ville|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French}}</ref>\n[[File:Tour_de_l'Horloge_-_castellane.jpg|thumb|left|Tour de l'Horloge]]\nConstruction on the wall enclosing the lower town began in 1359, with the permission of the [[Count of Provence]], [[Louis I of Naples]]. Traces of this wall are still visible in the square towers on the front of the houses on the square. [[Corbel]]s, which could support defenses ([[brattice]]s or simple [[parapet]]s with [[battlement]]s) are visible on their fa\u00e7ades.\n\nTwo of the original gates in the wall remain:\n*the gate of the Annunciation or of the ''p\u00e9tardiers'', flanked by two towers, high ground in the resistance of 1586;\n* the gate of the clock, also called St. Augustine's gate, set in a square tower. A passage crosses under the tower through an arch. The tower is listed on the register of historic places.\n\nOne of the towers in the Saint-Michel neighborhood has been home to a [[dovecote]] since 1585.\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n|2004|1592\n|2006|1630\n|2007|1604\n|2008|1579\n|2009|1553\n|2010|1537\n|2011|1565\n|2012|1557\n|2013|1549\n|2014|1541\n|2015|1543\n|2016|1547\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n[[File:Castellane Notre Dame du Roc.jpg|center|thumb|Castellane with the \u00c9glise St Denis on \"Le Roc\"]]\n[[File:Int\u00e9rieur_d'une_cuisine_ancienne_en_Haute-Provence,_Maison_Nature_et_Patrimoine_de_Castellane.jpg|center|thumb|An old Proven\u00e7al kitchen, reproduced at a Castellane museum]]\n[[File:France_PACA_04_Castellane_03.jpg|center|thumb|Sacred Heart church]]\n[[File:Map_commune_FR_insee_code_04039.png|center|thumb|Map of Castellane and surrounding communities]]\n\n==International relations==\n\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in France}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\n\nCastellane is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Pescasseroli]], Italy\n\n==See also==\n* [[Route Napol\u00e9on]]\n* [[House of Castellane]]\n*[[Communes of the Alpes-de-Haute-Provence department]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|P\u00e9tardiers}}\n\n*[http://www.insee.fr/en/home/home_page.asp INSEE]\n\n{{Commons category|Castellane}}\n{{Alpes-de-Haute-Provence communes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]]\n[[Category:Subprefectures in France]]\n[[Category:Neolithic sites]]\n[[Category:Gaul]]\n[[Category:War of the Austrian Succession]]\n[[Category:Architectural history]]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Europe]]\n[[Category:History of France by location]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the neighbourhood in [[Marseille]]|La Castellane}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name               = Castellane\n|commune status     = [[Subprefectures in France|Subprefecture]] and [[Communes of France|commune]]\n|image              = Fr- Castellane & Le Roc von oben.jpg\n|caption            = Castellane and Le Roc from above\n|image coat of arms = Blason Castellane.svg\n|arrondissement     = Castellane\n|canton             = Castellane\n|INSEE              = 04039\n|postal code        = 04120\n|mayor              = Jean-Pierre Terrien\n|term               = 2014\u20132020\n|intercommunality   = [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes Alpes Provence Verdon - Sources de Lumi\u00e8re|Alpes Provence Verdon \u2013 Sources de Lumi\u00e8re]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|43.8475|6.5139|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m        = 724\n|elevation min m    = 639\n|elevation max m    = 1761\n|area km2           = 117.79\n|population         = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date    = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}\n\n'''Castellane''' ({{IPA-fr|kast\u025blan}}; [[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]]: ''Castelana'') is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]] [[Departments of France|department]] in southeastern [[France]]. With about 1,600 inhabitants, Castellane has the distinction of being the least-populated sub-prefecture of France.\n\nIts inhabitants are referred to as ''Castellanais''.<ref>Roger Brunet, [http://tresordesregions.mgm.fr Canton of Castellane], ''Le Tr\u00e9sor des r\u00e9gions''</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCastellane is a very old city located upstream of the [[Verdon Gorge|Gorges du Verdon]]. The city is {{convert|724|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} [[above sea level]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Michel de La Torre |title= Alpes-de-Haute-Provence : le guide complet des 200 communes|location=Paris |publisher= Deslogis-Lacoste |work= Villes et villages de France |year=1989 |isbn=2-7399-5004-7}}</ref>\n\nThe Roc, or the Roc of Notre-Dame, overlooks the city from {{cvt|184|m|ft|0}} above.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Dichary|title=Castellane: \u00e0 l'aube des gorges du Verdon|publisher=Serre \u00c9diteur |location=Nice |year=1994 |language=French |trans-title=Castellane: At the Dawn of the Gorges of Verdon|isbn=978-2-86410-206-9 |page=7}}</ref> It has been occupied since the [[High Middle Ages]] and is a registered historical site. It can be accessed from the centre of town behind the old Church of St. Andrew. The walk takes about 25 minutes.\n[[File:Lac_de_Chaudanne.JPG|thumb|left|Lac de Chaudanne]]\nTwo reservoirs are located in the territory of Castellane:\n* [[Lac de Castillon|Lake Castillon]]\n* Lake Chaudanne, created by the dam of the same name, the {{Interlanguage link multi|Barrage de Chaudanne|fr}}.\nThe area has two [[water gap]]s: \n* the ''clue de Taulanne'' containing the [[Asse (river)|Asse de Blieux]] river and the [[Route Napol\u00e9on]] along its banks.\n* the ''clue de Chasteuil'', which contains the [[Verdon River|Verdon]] valley.\n[[File:Mobeye-\u00c9t\u00e9DesVilles-Castellane-366.jpg|thumb|left|Gorge of Castellane]]\nThe GR 4 hiking trail crosses through the town. The neighboring municipalities are:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Saint-Andr\u00e9-les-Alpes]]\n* [[Saint-Julien-du-Verdon]]\n* [[Demandolx]]\n* [[La Garde, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|La Garde]]\n* [[Ch\u00e2teauvieux, Var|Ch\u00e2teauvieux]]\n* [[Brenon]]\n* [[Le Bourguet]]\n* [[Trigance]]\n* [[Rougon]]\n* [[Blieux]]\n* [[Senez]]\n}}\n\n=== Climate ===\n\nCastellane features a [[mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: [[Hot-summer Mediterranean climate|Csa/Csb]]), bordering a cold [[humid continental climate|continental mediterraneran climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: [[Hot-summer humid continental climate|Dsa/Dsb]]). Summers are very hot and dry and winters are quite cold for a Mediterranean climate. Actually, Castellane's climate lays between two climates.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Digne-les-Bains, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, France\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|collapsed = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 22.8\n|Feb record high C = 23.7\n|Mar record high C = 25.8\n|Apr record high C = 27.6\n|May record high C = 31.8\n|Jun record high C = 35.6\n|Jul record high C = 37.3\n|Aug record high C = 37\n|Sep record high C = 33.4\n|Oct record high C = 29.7\n|Nov record high C = 23.3\n|Dec record high C = 20.3\n|year record high C = 37.3\n|Jan high C = 8.8\n|Feb high C = 10.7\n|Mar high C = 14\n|Apr high C = 15.9\n|May high C = 20.4\n|Jun high C = 24.8\n|Jul high C = 28.4\n|Aug high C = 27.8\n|Sep high C = 23.4\n|Oct high C = 18.5\n|Nov high C = 12.8\n|Dec high C = 8.6\n|year high C = 17.9\n|Jan mean C = 1.5\n|Feb mean C = 2.8\n|Mar mean C = 5.9\n|Apr mean C = 8.3\n|May mean C = 12.6\n|Jun mean C = 16.5\n|Jul mean C = 19.4\n|Aug mean C = 18.9\n|Sep mean C = 15\n|Oct mean C = 10.9\n|Nov mean C = 5.9\n|Dec mean C = 2\n|year mean C = 10\n|Jan low C = -5.7\n|Feb low C = -5.1\n|Mar low C = -2.1\n|Apr low C = 0.7\n|May low C = 4.8\n|Jun low C = 8.1\n|Jul low C = 10.3\n|Aug low C = 9.9\n|Sep low C = 6.6\n|Oct low C = 3.4\n|Nov low C = -1.1\n|Dec low C = -4.5\n|year low C = 2.1\n|Jan record low C = -20.5\n|Feb record low C = -18.8\n|Mar record low C = -19.0\n|Apr record low C = -9\n|May record low C = -4\n|Jun record low C = -0.8\n|Jul record low C = 2.5\n|Aug record low C = 1\n|Sep record low C = -2.2\n|Oct record low C = -9\n|Nov record low C = -15.5\n|Dec record low C = -19.5\n|year record low C = -20.5\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 67.1\n|Feb precipitation mm = 50.4\n|Mar precipitation mm = 51.5\n|Apr precipitation mm = 82.1\n|May precipitation mm = 92.2\n|Jun precipitation mm = 75.5\n|Jul precipitation mm = 42.4\n|Aug precipitation mm = 66.9\n|Sep precipitation mm = 91.9\n|Oct precipitation mm = 117.9\n|Nov precipitation mm = 109\n|Dec precipitation mm = 89\n|year precipitation mm = 935.9\n|unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 6.1\n|Feb precipitation days = 5.5\n|Mar precipitation days = 6.1\n|Apr precipitation days = 9.3\n|May precipitation days = 9.1\n|Jun precipitation days = 7.1\n|Jul precipitation days = 4.5\n|Aug precipitation days = 5.1\n|Sep precipitation days = 6.6\n|Oct precipitation days = 8.3\n|Nov precipitation days = 7.5\n|Dec precipitation days = 7.6\n|year precipitation days = 82.7\n|date=April 2019}}\n\n=== Geology ===\n{{See also|Geology of the Alps}}\nThe commune is part of the [[Jurassic]] [[limestone]] area of the [[French Prealps]] in [[Provence]], formed by the [[tectonics|tectonic]] upheaval of the Alps during the [[Tertiary]]. [[Limestone]] deposits run the length of the Verdon river, giving rise to spectacular gorges formed through [[karst]] [[erosion]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|author=Direction r\u00e9gionale de l'environnement (DIREN) \n|title=Les gorges du Verdon [archive]\n|work=Inventaire d\u00e9partemental des sites class\u00e9s\n|publisher=DIREN|date=October 2003\n|id= Accessed 24 August 2012\n}}</ref> Around Castellane older formations surface, such as [[gypsum]] and [[Triassic]] black [[marl]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Atlas des paysages des Alpes de Haute-Provence: Les Gorges du Verdon|page=443 |url=http://www.donnees.paca.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/docHTML/atlas04/files/4de/4de_33_fc.pdf|author=DREAL PACA, Direction R\u00e9gionale de 'Environnement, de'Am\u00e9nagement et du Logement, Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur|publisher=Pr\u00e9fet de la r\u00e9gion Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur|format=PDF|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 2008|title=Les gorges du Verdon: Contexte reglementaire|author=Direction r\u00e9gionale de l'environnement (DIREN PACA)|work=catalogue d\u00e9partemental des sites class\u00e9s, Var et Alpes de Haute-Provence|url=http://www.basecommunale.paca.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/pdf/fiches/sites_classes/93C00001.pdf}}</ref>\n\n'''Neighboring mountains and passes'''\n*Castellard ({{convert|1,725|m|ft|0|abbr=on|disp=or}})\n*Pr\u00e9 Chauvin ({{convert|1,741|m|ft|0|abbr=on|disp=or}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altituderando.com/Cadieres-de-Brandis-par-le-sommet|title=Cadi\u00e8res de Brandis par le sommet du Pr\u00e9 Chauvin (1741m)|language=French}}</ref>\n*{{Interlanguage link multi|L\u00e8ques Pass|fr|3=Col des L\u00e8ques}}, the route taken by [[Napoleon]]\n*Blaches Pass, on the road to [[Saint-Andr\u00e9-les-Alpes]]\n\n=== Environment ===\n[[File:Lac_de_castillon_la_colle.jpg|thumb|right|Lac de Castillon]]\nThe commune contains {{convert|7000|acres|abbr=off}} of wood and forests (about 59% of its surface area).<ref>\n{{Cite web\n|url=http://tresordesregions.mgm.fr/Mdir.php?p=cant.php&cl=Castellane&region=93\n|title=France, le tr\u00e9sor des r\u00e9gions\n|website=tresordesregions.mgm.fr\n|access-date=2016-04-27\n}}</ref> The {{Interlanguage link multi|Massif du Montdenier|fr}} extends over the western part of the commune (former communes of Taulanne, Chasteuil and Villars-Brandis).\n\n=== History of place names ===\n{{See also|Toponym}}\n[[File:Castellane_-_Petra_Castellana_-2.jpg|thumb|left|Petra Castellana]]\nCastellane's name appeared in texts for the first time circa 965\u2013977 as ''Petra Castellana''. The name breaks down into three [[Occitan]] terms, ''p\u00e8ira'', ''castel'' and the suffix ''-ana,'' which means fortified rock and village, and could be translated as \"Castellane rock\", in other words, the rock that has a fortified village,<ref name=EN>\n{{cite book\n|author=Ernest N\u00e8gre\n|title=Toponymie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la France: \u00e9tymologie de 35 000 noms de lieux, vol. 3 : Formations dialectales (suite); formations fran\u00e7aises\n|location=Geneva\n|publisher=Librairie Droz\n|work=Publications romanes et fran\u00e7aises\n|issue=195\n|year=1991\n|via=Google Books\n|isbn=2600028846\n}}|\u00a7 26663, pages=1465-1466\n</ref> or simply the stronghouse or stronghold. Castellane is called ''Castelana'' in the [[Proven\u00e7al dialect]] in the classical norm, or ''Castelano'' in the [[Mistralian norm|Mistralian]].\n[[File:Chasteuil-v.jpg|thumb|right|Village of Chasteuil]]\nThe former commune of Castillon, now beneath the lake, appeared around 1300 as ''de Castilhone'', an [[Occitan language|Occitan]] word for a small castle.<ref>\n{{cite book\n|author1=B\u00e9n\u00e9dicte F\u00e9ni\u00e9\n|author2=Jean-Jacques F\u00e9ni\u00e9\n|title=Toponymie proven\u00e7ale\n|publisher=\u00c9ditions Sud-Ouest\n|year=2002\n|isbn=978-2-87901-442-5\n| page=65\n}}</ref><ref>N\u00e8gre, op. cit., volume 3, \u00a7 26720, p 1470</ref>\n\nThe first part of the name \"Chasteuil\" is obscure, but the second, ''-ialo'', is a Celtic suffix for \"clearing\".<ref>F\u00e9ni\u00e9 & F\u00e9ni\u00e9, op. cit., p. 41</ref>\n\n[[File:Robion_calade.jpg|thumb|left|Robion]]\n\nThe village of ''Robion'' has the same name as the river that and flows through it  into the {{Interlanguage link multi|Jabron River|fr|3=Jabron_(affluent_du_Verdon)}} and takes its source from the Massif du Robion to the east of the village. The name ''in Rubione'', which first appeared for it in 1045, is derived from the vulgar Latin ''robigonem'', a distortion of the classical Latin ''robiginem'' for rust, according to [[Ernest N\u00e8gre]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ernest N\u00e8gre|title= Toponymie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la France: \u00e9tymologie de 35 000 noms de lieux, vol. 1: Formations pr\u00e9celtiques, celtiques, romanes |location=Geneva |publisher=Librairie Droz |work=Publications romanes et fran\u00e7aises |issue=193 |year=1990 |isbn=978-2-600-02884-4 |page=306|language=French|trans-title=General Toponymy of France: Etymology of 35,000 Place Names, vol.1: Celtic, Pre-Celtic and Roman Constructions}} \u00a7 5142</ref> [[Charles Rostaing]], on the other hand, believed that the name might predate the Gauls and designate a steep-sided ravine.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n{{Interlanguage link multi|Taloire|fr}}, was first mentioned in 1095 when the ch\u00e2teau of Taloire was given to the [[Abbey of St. Victor, Marseille]], which became the lay ''seigneur'' of the fief. It derived its name from the Occitan ''[[:fr:wikt:talador#Occitan|talador]]'', meaning soldiers especially recruited to devastate the land of an adversary. Adding the -ia suffix designates, either a land inhabited by these devastators, or a land devastated by the ''taladors''. Rostaing thought this name also probably also predated the Gauls. {{Interlanguage link multi|B\u00e9n\u00e9dicte and Jean-Jacques F\u00e9ni\u00e9|fr|3= F\u00e9ni\u00e9}} noted a [[tautology (grammar)|tautology]]: *Tal- et *Tor-, the ''teo'' roots. The name \"Taloire\" contains two terms designating a mountain.\n\n== Economy ==\nIn 2009, the unemployment rate of the Castellane population was 12.4%,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.insee.fr/fr/bases-de-donnees/?page=statistiques-locales.htm|title=Insee \u2013 Bases de donn\u00e9es \u2013 Donn\u00e9es locales|website=www.insee.fr|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> and there were 45 businesses in the secondary sector, with 84 paid workers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Prehistory and antiquity==\nThe inhabitants of Castellane are known back to a very early date. [[Neolithic]] [[nomad]]s came through the area; the oldest traces date back to 6000 BC. A grotto with [[cave painting]]s exists in the commune but its location is kept confidential to protect the artwork;<ref>{{cite book|author=Jean Gagnepain|title=Pr\u00e9histoire du Verdon, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence et Var: des origines \u00e0 la conqu\u00eate romaine |publisher=\u00c9disud |location=Aix-en-Provence|year=2002 |isbn=2-7449-0347-7 |language=fr| via=French Wikipedia, preface by Jean Courtin | page=75}}</ref> [[Bronze Age]] tombs have also been discovered in a cave in Castillon. [[Ligures|Ligurian]] tribes occupied the territory. The Suetrii or Su\u00e8tres later created an ''[[oppidum]]''{{efn|from the Latin \"oppidum\" (fortified camp on a hill).}}  named ''Ducelia'', near the Roc. They mined salt in the area and sold it. Most of the communes attached to Castellane today were peopled by the Suetrii.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/sracf_1159-7151_2004_act_25_1_1194|title= Castellane / Salinae (Alpes-de-Haute-Provence) |author=Guy Barruol|work=Capitales \u00e9ph\u00e9m\u00e8res. Des Capitales de cit\u00e9s perdent leur statut dans l'Antiquit\u00e9 tardive, Actes du colloque Tours 6\u20138 mars 2003{{!}} Supplement |publisher=Revue arch\u00e9ologique du centre de la France |year=2004|volume=25|number=1|pages=393\u2013395|language=French}}</ref> Taulanne was the exception, inhabited by the people who had their capital in [[Senez]]. (Their name is uncertain and Roman historians differ on the subject.<ref>See Guy Barruol, \u00ab Senez dans l'Antiquit\u00e9 \u00bb, in Juliette Hermellin, Senez en Haute-Provence, p. 15\u201317 and very long discussion of the topic at [https://books.google.com/books?id=kFFBAAAAcAAJ Charles G. de Bochat], ''M\u00e9moires Critiques, Pour servir d'Eclaircissements sur divers Points de L'Histoire Ancienne De La Suisse Et Sur Les Monumens D'Antiquit\u00e9 Qui la concernent''. Volume 1. Bousquet 1747, page 42.</ref>)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Brigitte Beaujard|title=Les cit\u00e9s de la Gaule m\u00e9ridionale du IIIe au VIIe si\u00e8cle|work=Gallia|issue=63|year=2006|publisher=CNRS \u00e9ditions| page=22}}</ref>\n[[File:CILXII,5437milliaireCastellane.jpg|thumb|right|Roman milestone]]\nThe region was conquered by [[Augustus]] in 14 BC. Castellane was attached to the Roman province of [[Alpes-Maritimes]] and began to grow. Homes were established in the plain, and the city was named ''Civitas Saliniensum'' (city of salt merchants). The name of the town later became Salinae.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BV1iAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA301|via=Google Books, British Library|title=The Classical Gazetteer: a Dictionary of Ancient Geography, Sacred and Profane|page=301|year=1851|language=English|author=William Hazlitt}}</ref>\n\nSeveral roads left from or passed through the town:\n* Via Salinaria, going west towards [[Durance]] and the current [[Ch\u00e2teau-Arnoux]] \n* Via Ventiana, from [[Cimiez]] to [[Sisteron]] by way of [[Vence]];<ref>{{cite news |title=A la rencontre du patrimoine : d\u00e9couverte de la carri\u00e8re Romaine: \u00c0 la recherche des milliaires oubli\u00e9s... au Col de Vence |work= Vence, cit\u00e9 d'Art et d'Azur |publisher= Ville de Vence |year=2016 |author= Marc Chaix}}</ref> a carved [[milestone]] from the beginning of the third century was found on this road in the Saint-Pierre pass<ref>{{cite book|title=La France: Collection des guides Joanne \u2013 guides diamant| author=Adolphe Joanne|edition=2|editor=Librairie Hachette et Cie |date=1873 |via=Google Books, Biblioth\u00e8que de Catalogne|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cwkapexu8XIC&pg=PR1}}</ref> six miles from Castellane\n* a fork towards [[Via Aurelia]] and Via [[Domitia]]\n* a road towards [[Entrevaux]] ([[Gland\u00e8ves]]) by way of [[Brian\u00e7onnet]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archeam.fr/sites/www.archeam.fr/files/pdf/archeam7/archeam_7_chavane_voie_romaine_castellane_brianconnet_entrevaux.pdf|title=Description d'une voie romaine reliant Castellane a Brian\u00e7onnet et Entrevaux (Gland\u00e8ves)&#124;Vincent Chavanne|work=Arch\u00e9ologia|date=November 1995|language=French|trans-title=Description of a Roman Road Linking Castellane to Brian\u00e7onnet and Entrevaux (Gland\u00e8ves)}}</ref>\n\nResidents first settled on the bank of the Verdon to mine the saline sources which are still visible today. A treasure of antiquity, 34 gold coins issued by [[Arcadius]] and [[Honorius (emperor)|Honorius]], were discovered in 1797 in Taloire. A limestone funerary stele for one Julius Trofimus, dating back to Roman times, was discovered near the old chapel of Notre-Dame-du-Plan. Until 1942 it was used in a retaining wall, and can be found today in the public garden of the savings bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000058 |title=Mobilier |year=1992 |work=Palissy database|publisher=minist\u00e8re fran\u00e7ais de la Culture}}</ref> The inscription is included in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Inscriptions latines de Gaule narbonnaise|fr}} (ILGN) collection of [[Gallia Narbonensis]] Roman inscriptions and is listed on the historic register.\n\nA diocese was founded in the fifth century: its seat was transferred to Senez before the 6th century however and despite all attempts to have it return to Castellan it remained there until it was closed in the French Revolution.\n\n==Middle Ages==\n[[File:Castellane_Notre_Dame_du_Roc2.jpg|thumb|left]]\nIn the early ninth century, the area around the current town of Castellane was inhabited by only 84 people. In 812 the area was invaded by Moors, also sometimes called Saracens; they destroyed ''Salines'', the early settlement near the salt marshes.<ref name=gros>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7flPwL6Da9sC |title=Antiquit\u00e9s de l'arrondissement de Castellanne |edition=2 |via=University of Oxford, Google Books |year=1842 |author= Gras-Bourguet |publisher= Digne |language=French}}</ref> The inhabitants of Salines took refuge on the summit of the Roc and built a stronghold there, building the first Notre-Dame there, inaugurated in 852, in thanks for the refuge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basecommunale.paca.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/pdf/fiches/sites_classes/93C04004.pdf |title=CASTELLANE: LE ROC NOTRE-DAME |author=DIREN PACA |work=catalogue d\u00e9partemental des sites class\u00e9s, Alpes de Haute-Provence|year=2003}}</ref> Some vestiges of this site, which was named ''Sinaca'' in 813 and ''Petra Castellana'' in 965, are still visible at the place now known as ''Le Signal''. People later also settled at the foot of the Roc in the valley bottom.\n\nIn 852 a lord of Castellane, possibly named Guillaume<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EVk_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA115|via=Bibliotheque cant. et univ. Lausanne, Google Books|page=115|title=Dictionnaire g\u00e9ographique, historique et politique des Gaules et de la France|author=Jean-Joseph Expilly|year=1764|publisher=Desaint & Saillant|trans-title=Geographical, Historical and Political Dictionary of the Gauls and of France}}</ref> won a victory against the Moors and put together a barony of 46 village communities stretching from [[Cotignac]] in [[Var (department)|Var]] to the south, to [[Thorame-Haute]] in the north, and from [[Soleilhas]] to [[Esparron-de-Verdon]].<!-- from french wikipedia, <s>still needs a reference --> Over time Castellane came to have three co-existing sites:\n*the Rupes, on top of the Rock, was soon entirely occupied by the castle built in 977 by Pons-Arbaud and [[Aldebert]]<!-- date problem, alive much earlier (?) -->\n*the Castrum, halfway up, on a larger site but easy to defend;\n*the Burgum, current site of Castellane, easily accessible, facilitating trade.<ref name=HB>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rfNpxIJUikQC&pg=PA276|page=913|title=La chorographie ou description de Prouence et l'histoire chronologique du mesme pays. Tome premier (-second). Par le sieur Honor\u00e9 Bouch\u00e9|via=Carmelitani: Biblioteca Torino, Google Books|year=1664|language=French}}</ref>\n[[File:Ch\u00e2teau_de_Rougon_3.JPG|thumb|right|Ruined ch\u00e2teau in Rougon]]\nIn 1189, Baron de Castellane Boniface III was attacked by [[Alfonso II of Aragon|Alfonso I of Provence]]. He had refused to do homage, explaining that he was a vassal of the Holy Roman Empire. But in the face of brute force he was forced to bend the knee. Another war broke out in 1227 between the Provence and Boniface of Castellane, presumably the son.<ref>{{cite book |title= La chorographie ou description de Prouence et l'histoire chronologique du mesme pays. Tome premier (-second). Par le sieur Honor\u00e9 Bouch\u00e9 |author= Honor\u00e9 Bouch\u00e9  |date=1664 |via= Google Books, University of Turin (Carmelitani: Biblioteca Torino) |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=rfNpxIJUikQC&pg=PP7 |page= 919}}</ref> In 1257 Charles II\u2014then still just prince of Salernes, gave the castle to the Austinian monks. In 1262, [[Charles I of Naples|Charles I of Anjou]] defeated [[Bonifaci VI de Castellana|Boniface of Castellane]] and made Castelle the seat of a [[:fr:wikt:baile#Ancien occitan|baile]]. In the thirteenth century, the family of Castellane lost possession of the city to the Counts of Provence. To protect themselves from attack, in addition to the protections for the city, Castellane built a series of fortified outposts at [[Demandolx]], [[La Garde, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|La Garde]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Chasteuil|fr}}, [[Rougon]], and perhaps Taloire.{{when|date=September 2016}} In 1300 a small Jewish community of eight households was established in the area.<ref>{{cite book|author=\u00c9douard Baratier|title=La d\u00e9mographie proven\u00e7ale du XIIIe au XVIe si\u00e8cles, avec chiffres de comparaison pour le XVIIIe si\u00e8cle|location=Paris|publisher=SEVPEN/EHESS|year=1961|work=Collection D\u00e9mographie et soci\u00e9t\u00e9|number=5| page=70|language=French|trans-title=Proven\u00e7al Demography in from the 13th to the 16th century, with numbers compared to the 18th century}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Black Death]] reached Castellane in 1348, and was followed by a devastating flood of the [[Verdon River]]. The capture and death of Queen [[Joanna I of Naples]] created a succession issue in the county of Provence, the cities of the [[Union of Aix]] (1382\u20131387) supporting [[Charles III of Naples|Charles de Duras]] against [[Louis I, Duke of Anjou|Louis I of Anjou]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n|title=Volume 1 of Inventaire sommaire des archives communales ant\u00e9rieures \u00e0 1790\n|work=Inventaire sommaire des archives communales ant\u00e9rieures \u00e0 1790\n|author=Ministry of the Interior, France\n|publisher=Imprimerie E. Aurel\n|year=1866\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7sNEAQAAMAAJ\n|via=Google Books and University of Chicago\n|page=393\n}}\n</ref>\n[[File:Castellane_-_Ch\u00e2teau_d'\u00c9oulx_-3.JPG|thumb|left|Ch\u00e2teau_d'\u00c9oulx]]\nLord of Castellane Louis d'Anduse, also often known<ref>{{cite book|page=16|title=Annales de Haute Provence| language=French |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yXI2AAAAMAAJ |author=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 scientifique et litt\u00e9raire des Basses-Alpes |location=Digne|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 scientifique et litt\u00e9raire des Alpes-de-haute-provence |year=1894 |via=University of Michigan, Google Books|volume=6}}</ref> as Lord of La Voulte,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2gU9AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA169|title=Nobiliaire universel de France: ou Recueil g\u00e9n\u00e9ral des g\u00e9n\u00e9alogies historiques des maisons nobles de ce royaume, Volume 3 |language=French|page=169|via=Google Books, University of California|author1=M. de Saint-Allais (Nicolas Viton)|author2=Ange Jacques Marie Poisson de La Chabeaussi\u00e8re |author3=Jean Baptiste Pierre Jullien de Courcelles|author4=Lespines (abb\u00e9 de), Ducas Johann Lanz|publisher=bureau du Nobiliaire universel de France, R\u00e9imprim\u00e9 \u00e0 la Librairie Bachelin-Deflorenne |year=1873}}</ref> sided with the [[Louis I, Duke of Anjou|Duke of Anjou]] from the spring of 1382, supporting him on condition he participate in an expedition to rescue the queen.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Genevi\u00e8ve Xhayet|title=Partisans et adversaires de Louis d'Anjou pendant la guerre de l'Union d'Aix|work=Provence historique|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration historique de Provence|volume=40|issue=162, \"Autour de la guerre de l'Union d'Aix\"|year=1990|pages=417\u2013419}}</ref> Castellane itself initially also backed the Duke, but changed allegiance in February 1386 after the Duke died, and rallied to the cause of the queen-regent, [[Marie of Blois, Duchess of Anjou|Marie de Blois]]. She negotiated with them, hoping to set off a chain of similar declarations of support. Guillaume de Forcalquier and his son Jean Raynaut, lords of Eoulx, submitted to the Duchess in July 1386. In 1390, {{Interlanguage link multi|Raymond de Turenne|fr|3=Raimond de Turenne}} ravaged the surrounding territory and the village of Taulanne and failed to take the city, but did destroy the wooden bridge over the Verdon River.\n[[File:Castellane_-180.jpg|thumb|right|Pont du Roc]]\nThe wooden bridge over the Verdon was rebuilt in stone in the 15th century. A [[Bridge-Building Brotherhood|monastery]] took care of its maintenance.<ref>{{cite book|author=Baratier, Duby & Hildesheimer|title=Les \u00e9tablissements des ordres militaires et hospitaliers en Provence (XIIIe-XIVe si\u00e8cles)| page=map 68}}</ref> The bridge on the Place Castellane put Castellane on the frequently travelled routes between the  Mediterranean and the bridge over the [[Durance]] river at [[Sisteron]]. The bridge toll for the Verdon and the fair began at the end of the Middle Ages. The fair continued until the end of the ''[[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]'', assuring the town relative prosperity.\n\nIn the fifteenth century, a community settled on the present site of Taloire. In the middle of the fifteenth century, the upper village was completely abandoned in favor of the lowland site.\n\n==Renaissance==\n[[File:Draille.JPG|thumb|right|Draille in Robion]]\nAt the end of the Middle Ages, the [[transhumance]] system developed enormously, herds of sheep from the coast going up into the high Alpine valleys in the summer. Some ''[[drover's road|drailles]]'' (herding routes) crossed the Castellane bridge, where a toll was instituted. At the beginning of the 16th century, between 78,000 and 120,000 head were crossing each year during May and June.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pierre Coste|author2=No\u00ebl Coulet|title=Que sait-on des origines de la transhumance en Provence?|editor1=Jean-Claude Duclos|editor2=Andr\u00e9 Pitte|work=L'homme et le mouton dans l'espace de la transhumance (Man and Sheep in Transhumance)|location=Grenoble|publisher=Gl\u00e9nat|year=1994|isbn=2-7234-1746-8| page=68|trans-title=What is known of the origin of transhumance in Provence?|language=French}}</ref>\n[[File:Jakob_Seisenegger_001.jpg|thumb|left|Charles V]]\nThe imperial army of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] pillaged the town en 1536.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michel de La Torre|title=Alpes-de-Haute-Provence: le guide complet des 200 communes|trans-title=Alpes-de-Haute-Provence: Complete Guide to the 200 communes|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=Deslogis-Lacoste|work=collection \"Villes et villages de France\"|year=1989|isbn=2-7399-5004-7}}</ref>\n\nReligious unrest broke out in 1559. Brun de Caille had converted some of the townspeople of Castellane, who gathered at his home for services. A sectarian skirmish took place at his home.<ref name=gros/> [[Huguenot]] captain {{Interlanguage link multi|Paulon de Mauvans|fr}}, of another rich Protestant family, sacked the town in the summer of 1560,<ref>{{cite book|author=Pierre Miquel |title=Les Guerres de Religion |trans-title=The Wars of Religion|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=Club France Loisirs|year=1980|isbn=2-7242-0785-8| page=211}}</ref> then established himself there after reaching an armistice with the governor of Provence, the count of [[Tende]], [[Claude of Savoy]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} <!-- based on dates in wikipedia articles --> The town was attacked by Protestants on 4 October 1574, but the residents of Castellane and its surroundings chased them off, pursuing them as far as the ''clue de Taulanne''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jacques Cru|title=Histoire des Gorges du Verdon jusqu'\u00e0 la R\u00e9volution|trans-title=History of the Gorges of the Verdon| page=200}}</ref>\nOn 30 January 1586, the {{Interlanguage link multi|Baron of Allemagne|fr|3=Nicolas_Mas-Castellane}} and the [[Fran\u00e7ois de Bonne, Duke of Lesdigui\u00e8res|Duke of Lesdigui\u00e8res]] tried to surprise the town. The sneak attack was repulsed and the Baron d'Allemagne was injured by a bullet in his back, which caused the assailants to retreat. The Baron was killed in September of that year trying to lift the siege of his own castle, shot in the head by an [[arquebus]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=XVe journ\u00e9e arch\u00e9ologique|work=Annales de Haute-Provence|volume=308 2e trimestre|year=1989| pages=17\u201318}}</ref>\nThe end of the siege of Castellane has since been celebrated every year in the last weekend of January with the ''P\u00e9tardiers'' ceremony reenacting the attack, and notably the episode of Judith Andr\u00e9 or Andrau, the goodwife of [[Barr\u00eame]],<ref>{{cite book|author=J.-F. Cruvellier|title=Histoire de Barr\u00eame|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 scientifique et litt\u00e9raire des Basses-Alpes| page=4}}</ref> who killed ''p\u00e9tardier'' captain Jean Motte by pouring a kettle of boiling peas over him from the top of the ''porte de l'Annonciade'', reputed to be the weak point in the defenses.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jacques Cru|title=Histoire des Gorges du Verdon jusqu'\u00e0 la R\u00e9volution| page=203}}</ref>\ns1z\n\n==17th and 18th century==\nThe [[plague (disease)|plague]] struck the town again in 1630.\n\nThe [[Jansenist]] bishop [[Jean Soanen]] tried to make the celebrations of [[Corpus Christi (feast)|Saint-Sacrement]], [[Nativity of St John the Baptist|Saint-Jean]] and [[Saint Eligius|Saint-\u00c9loi]] more sedate and less unbridled, the youth of the town having a tradition of celebrating with drums, music and gunshots. The youth refused, resisted, made even more noise and even revolted, preventing the procession of the octave du Saint-Sacrement from leaving the church on June 22, 1710.<ref name=nic>{{cite book|author=Jean Nicolas|title=La R\u00e9bellion fran\u00e7aise: mouvements populaires et conscience sociale, 1661\u20131789 |language=French|trans-title=The French Rebellion: Popular Movements and Social Conscience |location=Paris |publisher= Gallimard |year=2008 |series= Collection Folio |isbn= 978-2-07-035971-4 | page=703}}</ref> In 1726 the youth of Robion, whom the priest wanted to prevent from dancing on Sunday, also revolted.<ref name=nic/>\n[[File:Castellane,_D4085,_clue_de_Taulanne,_du_sud.jpg|thumb|left|Clue de Taulanne]]\nThe Austrian-Sardinian army briefly occupied the town in 1746 during the [[war of the Austrian Succession]]. In December 1746, Provence was invaded by an Austrian-Sardinian army. A troop of 2,000 men took Castellane,<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pierre Grillon|title=L'invasion et la lib\u00e9ration de la Provence en 1746\u20131747|work=Provence historique|volume=12|issue=50|year=1962|page=345|language=French|trans-title=The invasion and liberation of Provence in 1746\u20131747}}</ref> then the surrounding villages, as far as the ch\u00e2teau of [[Trigance]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pierre Grillon|title=L'invasion et la lib\u00e9ration de la Provence en 1746\u20131747|work=Provence historique|volume=12|issue=50|year=1962|page=353|language=French|trans-title=The invasion and liberation of Provence in 1746\u20131747}}</ref> After some difficulty, the Spanish and French armies coordinated a counteroffensive, which began at the start of January when French soldiers under the orders of the [[Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing|Count of Maul\u00e9vrier]] took an Austrian outpost in Chasteuil.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pierre Grillon|title=L'invasion et la lib\u00e9ration de la Provence en 1746\u20131747|work=Provence historique|volume=12|issue=50|year=1962|page=352|language=French|trans-title=The invasion and liberation of Provence in 1746\u20131747}}</ref> The Austrian commander, [[Maximilian Ulysses Browne]], reinforced his right wing with four battalions garrisoned at Castellane, and six on the south bank of the Verdon. Seven other battalions formed a second available squadron. Nine battalions and ten squads of Spaniards were stationed in [[Riez]] and 2,500 Swiss paid by Spain were stationed at Senez. The 21st of January, Hispano-French troops went on the offensive, commanded by the Frenchman Maul\u00e9vrier and the Spanish Marquis of Taubin.<ref>\n{{cite book\n|title=The History of the War of MDCCXLI.: Containing the History of that War Till the Peace of Aix-la-Chapelle in 1748. In Three Parts. By M. de Voltaire. To which is Annexed, a Particular Account of the Rise, Progress, and Extinction of the Rebellion in G. Britain in 1745 and 1746\n|editor=W. Gray\n|year=1758\n|via=British Library, Google Books\n|page=258\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EZDY2ky-WmsC&pg=PA258\n}}\n</ref> The Spanish left their quarters by night and advanced on Castellane through the ''clue de Taulanne'', while the French passing through the Vodon gorge. The difficult marches necessary to approach in this way nonetheless allowed a coordinated attack around 7am.\n\nThe first outposts were taken without difficulty, which allowed Maul\u00e9vrier to connect on his left with Taubin, and to send a column of [[dragoons]] onto the right bank to cut the Austrians' retreat. This assault took the Austrian-Sardinians fortifications without difficulty, the French-Spanish entered the town and did prevent the last Austrians from retreating. In all, they took 287 Austrians prisoner, including the baron de Neuhaus,<ref>{{cite book|page=173|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DTZbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA173|title=Lettres historiques: contenant ce qui se passe de plus important en Europe et les r\u00e9flexions n\u00e9cessaires sur ce sujet..., Volume 122|author1=Jacques Bernard|author2=Henri Basnage (sieur de Beauval)|author3=Jean du Mont |editor=Adrian Moetjens|year=1747|language=French|via=Google Books, Universit\u00e9 de Gand}}</ref> the lieutenant-general in command. The Austrian-Sardinians also had a hundred-odd dead, versus twenty Franco-Spanish soldiers. The villages of La Garde, Eoulx, Robion, Taloire, Trigance and Comps were evacuated on January 22.\n[[File:FR_Var_Trigance_old_street.JPG|thumb|right|Street in Trigance]]\nIn 1760, a tax imposed by the king of Piedmont-Sardinia on sales of cloth brought a large reduction in the town's textile production. Production of {{Interlanguage link multi|cadis|fr}}, a local form of wool, and of ''cordeillat'', a coarse woolen fabric, continued until the Revolution, and was used by the local residents.\n\nUntil the Revolution salt was produced from two local salt marshes.\n\nOn the eve of the [[French Revolution]], several [[fiefs]] existed on the actual territory of the commune: \u00c9oulx, Le Castellet-de-Robion (which became a [[feudal barony|barony]] in 1755), Chasteuil, Taulanne and Castillon, plus Castellane. On the same territory there were nine [[parish]]es: Castillon, La Baume, Taulanne, La Palud, Chasteuil, Taloire, Villars-Brandis, Robion, et Castellane. The parish of \u00c9oulx overlapped the community of La Garde.\n\nThe city of Castellane alone paid more tax than [[Digne]]; it was an important rural town, both for its judiciary functions (with eight lawyers and five prosecutors) and for its production, with twelve factories: among which were six hat shops, two wax factories, one fa\u00efence works, one tile factory, one silk fabrication works, and the leather industry was also represented.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pr\u00e9fecture des Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|title=Histoire de la Sous-Pr\u00e9fecture de Castellane|publisher=Pr\u00e9fecture des Alpes de Haute-Provence}}</ref> A royal post office was also installed in Castellane near the end of the ''[[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=\u00c9mile Lauga|title=La poste dans les Basses-Alpes, ou l'histoire du courrier de l'Antiquit\u00e9 \u00e0 l'aube du XXe si\u00e8cle|language=French|trans-title=Postal Service in the Basses-Alpes, or the History of Mail from Antiquity to the Dawn of the 20th Century|location=Digne-les-Bains|publisher=\u00c9ditions de Haute-Provence|year=1994|isbn=2-909800-64-4| page=58}}</ref>\n\n==19th century==\n[[File:Le_Commerce...Quand_donc..._LACMA_M.91.82.251.jpg|thumb|left|Political cartoon in ''Le Charivari'', 2 December 1851. The caption says \"When are you going to stop playing these games? I am getting tired of paying for them.\"]]\nThe cloth industry, already well established in the preceding century, prospered in the first half of the 19th century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Raymond Collier|title=La Haute-Provence monumentale et artistique|location=Digne|publisher=Imprimerie Louis Jean|year=1986|page=414}}</ref> But cottage industries were replaced by the Barneaud factory, built in the late 1830s on the model of the Honnorat factory in [[Saint-Andr\u00e9-les-Alpes|Saint-Andr\u00e9-de-M\u00e9ouilles]]. It employed nine workers in 1872, then disappeared in 1878.<ref>{{cite thesis|author=Mireille Mistral\n|title=L'industrie drapi\u00e8re dans la all\u00e9e du Verdon |type=doctoral |publisher=Acad\u00e9mie d'Aix-en-Provence|location=Nice|year=1951|page=41}}</ref>\n\nThe Revolution and the Empire brought social reforms, including proportional taxation based on the assets. In order to put this in place on a precise basis, a land registry was drawn up. The ''loi de finances du 15 septembre 1807'' specified its methods, but its accomplishment took time to get started, since the officials conducting the ''[[cadastre]]'' dealt with the ''communes'' in successive geographic groups. Not until 1834\u20131835 was the land registry known as the Napoleonic cadastre of Castellane and its associated communes finished.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Alexe\u00ef Laurent|title=Paysages ruraux de la premi\u00e8re moiti\u00e9 du XIXe si\u00e8cle dans le sud-est des Basses-Alpes|editor=Jean-Christophe Labadie|series=''La mati\u00e8re et le b\u00e2ti en Haute-Provence, XVIIIe-XXIe si\u00e8cle'', proceedings of the first History of Haute-Provence Day (Journ\u00e9e d'\u00e9tudes d'histoire de la Haute-Provence), Digne, 13 October 2012|work=Digne-les-Bains: Archives d\u00e9partementales des Alpes-de-Haute-Provence|year=2013|isbn=978-2-86004-016-7| page=10}}</ref>\n\nThe [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] of 2 December 1851 committed by Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte against the [[French Second Republic|Second Republic]] provoked an armed uprising in the [[Basses-Alpes]] in defense of the Constitution. Insurgent republicans took a number of cities in the center and south of France, including [[Digne]], the prefecture of the [[Basses-Alpes]], and held them for several days. The local fighters held out the longest, almost three weeks. But this allowed Bonaparte to portray himself as the protector of France, and many participants were sent to penal colonies in [[Lambesa]] and [[Cayenne]], banished or less permanently exiled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cairn.info/revue-parlements1-2009-2-page-24.htm#no34|title=Le coup d\u2019\u00c9tat du 2 d\u00e9cembre 1851 ou la chronique de deux morts annonc\u00e9es et l\u2019av\u00e8nement d\u2019un grand principe|author=Eric Anceau|work=Parlement[s], Revue d'histoire politique |year=2009 |volume=12 |publisher=L'Harmattan|issn=1760-6233 |language=French}}</ref> Eight inhabitants of Castellane were brought before the ''commission mixte''; their most common penalty was deportation to Algeria.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Henri Joannet|author2=Jean-Pierre Pinatel|title=Arrestations-condamnations 1851|trans-title=Arrests-Convictions 1851|work=Pour m\u00e9moire, Les M\u00e9es: Les Amis des M\u00e9es|year=2001|page=71}}</ref>\n\n==20th century==\n[[File:RN_85,_st\u00e8le_col_des_L\u00e8ques.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial to FTP fighters]]\nOn 10 September 1926, the sous-pr\u00e9fecture was eliminated in the economic plan of [[Raymond Poincar\u00e9]], then re-established by the [[Vichy government]] in June 1942.\n\nAn [[internment]] camp was built in Chaudanne during [[World War II]]. Seventeen Jews were arrested in Castellane and deported. On 9 December 1943, the French [[arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te]] (AS) and the [[Francs-tireurs et partisans]] (FTP) attacked the construction site at the Castillon dam and seized five tonnes of explosives.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Jean Garcin|title=La r\u00e9sistance arm\u00e9e|work=Basses-Alpes|volume=39\u201345|issue=7|date=July 2004| page=4|language=French|trans-title=Armed Resistance}}</ref>\n\nThe ''commune'' was liberated 18 August 1944 by the [[36th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|36th division]] of British infantry.\n\nIn the mid-20th century [[viticulture|wine growing]] for local consumption ended.\n\n==Sites and monuments==\n[[File:Castellane_-176.jpg|thumb|right|The Roc and the bridge of the Roc]]\nThe Rock which dominates the city, rising to {{convert|930|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} (over {{convert|200|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} above the Verdon), is a listed historical  site.\n\nThe oldest monument in the territory of the commune is the [[dolmen]] of Pierres Blanches<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00132925|title=Architecture|date=April 16, 1996|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise}}</ref> Neolithic-Chalcolithic,  a registered historical site on private property. The Roc towers {{convert|184|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} above the community of Castellane.\n\nThe Mus\u00e9e des sir\u00e8nes et fossiles and the Moyen Verdon is networked with other museums in the Gorges du Verdon, including the home of Pauline Gr\u00e9oux-les-Bains, the museum of the life of yesteryear Esparron-de-Verdon, home gorges du Verdon in La Palud-sur-Verdon and the Museum of prehistory in Quinson gorges du Verdon.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Antibes Castellane.JPG|thumb|right|In the city of Castellane]]\n\nThe bridge of the Roc, which carries the [[Sisteron]]-[[Vence]] road across the river, was built in the first decade of the fifteenth century, replacing a succession of several wooden bridges, the last spanning the Verdon in 1300 and destroyed by {{Interlanguage link multi|Raimond de Turenne|fr}} in 1390. The construction of the new bridge parallels that of [[Nyons]] (built in 1401, {{convert|42|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long), Pont de Claix (built in 1607\u201313, {{convert|45|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long), [[Tournon-sur-Rh\u00f4ne|Tournon]] (built in the sixteenth century, {{convert|49|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long) and [[Entrechaux]] ({{convert|24.5|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} long). [[Pope Benedict XIII]] granted [[indulgence]]s to anyone who gave [[alms]] to finance its construction.<ref>{{cite book|author=Serge Montens|title=Les plus beaux ponts de France|location=Paris |publisher=Bonneton |year=2001 |isbn=2-86253-275-4 |page=15}}</ref> The [[rearguard]] of the Austrian-Sardinian army was caught there by a [[sortie]] from the [[garrison]].\n[[File:France_PACA_04_Castellane_06.jpg|thumb|left|Bridge of the Roc]]\nThe [[tympanum (architecture)|tympana]] of the Roc bridge have been restored several times. Metal [[tie rod]]s were laid in 1697\u201399. The bridge as a whole was restored in 2008 and closed to traffic. It was decommissioned in 1967 and delisted in 1982. The bridge and its approaches have been a registered historical site since 1940.\n\nThe library is in the former convent of the [[Order of the Visitation of Holy Mary|Visitation]], founded in 1644. The eighteenth-century castle at \u00c9oulx is richly decorated with plasterwork, including the first floor ceilings, the panels surrounding the doors, the rosette in the second-floor ceilings. Externally, it has two towers, with arched openings. The town hall is housed in the building that used to be the savings bank. It resembles a villa: balconies supported by large [[corbel]]s and thick [[baluster]]s, and a fa\u00e7ade adorned with a [[pediment]].\n\nCatellane's largest fountain, in the main square, features a pyramid on which is carved a compass crossed by a [[carpenter's square]], two [[chisel]]s and a [[mallet]], emblems of the [[Freemasons]]. At the top of the pyramid is a [[pedestal]] with a ball. On National Street, two doors have [[transom (architectural)|transom]]s or capitals with [[volute]]s, and one [[lintel]] is decorated with carved foliage. In the town, several buildingss, mostly dry stone, have been recorded in the inventory of topographic DRAC. One of them, in Rayaup, dates from the eighteenth century (the inscription that says 1586 is very recent).\n\n==Notre-Dame du Roc==\n[[File:Castellane_7_chapelleNDduRoc.jpg|thumb|left|Notre Dame du Roc]]\nThe Chapel of Our Lady of the Rock, dating from the High Middle Ages, dominates the city from atop the Rock and belongs to the former Convent of Mercy. But only the wall and the south fa\u00e7ade date from the twelfth century; the building was half demolished during the [[French wars of religion|wars of religion]] and rebuilt in 1590.\n\nCrumbling by 1703, the chapel was again rebuilt in the early eighteenth century and once more in 1860. A capital adorned with foliage and scrolls dates from the Renaissance.\n[[File:Castellane_7_chapelleNDduRoc2.jpg|thumb|right]]\nThe furnishings include:\n*a statue of the Virgin, in marble, possibly 16th century \n*two paintings, ''St. Charles Borromeo'' and ''St. Francis and St. Jeanne de Chantal'', on the historic register for both the paintings and their gilded frames, bearing the arms of the Bishop of Senez Ducha\u00eene and dating from the seventeenth century.\n\nIt received numerous [[votive offering]]s in the 19th and 20th centuries, including:\n[[File:Castellane_7_chapelleNDduRoc3.jpg|thumb|left|Votive offerings]]\n*traditional engraved plates (136 total);\n*bridal bouquets (21 total);\n*a painting given after a vow to Our Lady, dating from 1757, and registered;\n*a painting given after the cholera epidemic in 1835, registered;\n*a painting given by a released prisoner, dated 1875 (registered);\n*a painting given in thanks after a smallpox epidemic, dated 1870, registered;\n*a painting given by a person who escaped a shipwreck in 1896, registered.\n\n==Saint-Victor==\n[[File:\u00c9glise_Saint-Victor_-_Castellane.jpg|thumb|right|Saint Victor]]\nParts of the old parish church of Saint-Victor date from the mid-11th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00080359|title=Architecture: Eglise Saint-Victor|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French|date=June 4, 1993}}</ref> It is listed as an historical building. It was constructed in a similar manner and on the same plane as the Church of St. Andrew in the old village above the modern-day town, and was formerly the seat of a [[priory]] of the [[Abbey of St. Victor, Marseille|Abbey of St. Victor]] in Marseille.\n\nThe [[apse]] is decorated with [[Lombard band]]s, which have been described as remarkable,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/ccmed_0007-9731_1977_num_20_77_2053|title=Survivances du premier art roman en Provence &#124; Surviving Traces of Early Roman Art in Provence|author=Victor Lassalle|work=Cahiers de civilisation m\u00e9di\u00e9vale|year=1977 |volume=20 |issue=77 |page=6|via=Pers\u00e9e|language=French}}</ref> each arch carved from a single stone. Unusually for the region, it has a Roman [[nave]], with arches rebuilt in the 17th century. The base of the tower dates from 1445, but its top was rebuilt in the 18th century following damage by Protestants in 1560.\n\nThe altar dates from 1724. The choir is adorned with paintings framed in wood, and an [[Annunciation]] carved in [[relief#high relief|relief]] from gilded wood (18th century, on historical register). The wooden furniture, the stalls, the pulpit and the lectern with its hexagonal base, form an interesting 18th and 19th-century set, some of which is on the historic register. The furnishings also include an early 17th-century silver chalice with an unusual multilobed foot, also on the historic register.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000641|title=Mobilier: calice|date=July 20, 2000|work=Palissy database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Other historic churches==\n[[File:Castellane_-_Sacr\u00e9-Coeur_-1.jpg|thumb|left|Sacr\u00e9-Coeur]]\n[[File:Castellane_-_\u00c9glise_paroissiale_Saint-Pons_d'\u00c9oulx_-3.JPG|thumb|right|Saint Pons in \u00c9oulx]]\n[[File:Castellane,_\u00e9glise_Saint-Pierre_de_Taulanne,_fa\u00e7ade.jpg|thumb|right|Saint Pierre de Taulanne]]\n*The Church of the Sacred Heart, now a parish church, was built in 1868\u20131873 by Father Pougnet and dedicated to Our Lady. It was widened by side aisles in 1896. The first [[transept]] is occupied by a platform. <!-- ? dais? -translator --> The interior is [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]], with the tower built against the fa\u00e7ade. The furnishings include some registered historical items:two silver ''custodes'', cases for carrying [[communion (sacrament)|communion]] hosts; one dating from around 1650<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000642|work=Palissy database|date=July 20, 2000|title=Mobilier: ciboire-chrismatoire (custode)|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise}}</ref> and one from the 18th century, a gilded wooden 18th-century cross,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000507|title=Mobilier: croix (crucifix)|date=January 29, 1990|work=Palissy database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de culture fran\u00e7ais}}</ref> and a 16th-century silver [[chalice]]\n[[File:Castellane_-_Chapelle_Saint-Antoine_d'\u00c9oulx_-1.JPG|thumb|left|Saint Antoine of \u00c9oulx]]\n*the Chapel of St. Joseph is part of the Augustinian church rebuilt to replace the chapel of the [[Blue Penitents]]. It was partly demolished to widen the boulevard Saint-Michel\n*the 12th-century {{Interlanguage link multi|Saint Thyrse Chapel|fr|3=Chapelle Saint-Thyrse de Robion}} near Robion was restored in 1942 and declared a historical monument in 1944,<ref>{{cite web|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e|title=Inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral du patrimoine culturel |language=French |trans-title=General Inventory of the Cultural Heritage|author=Ronsseray, Dominique|date=March 26, 2010}}</ref> It is the earliest Romanesque (11th and 12th centuries) church in the region. \n*Saint-Pons in Eoulx, unchanged since its construction, not arched, has preserved the original [[cornice]]s from the middle or late twelfth century, also the thirteenth century according to the [[Direction r\u00e9gionale des affaires culturelles]] (DRAC). This building is on the historic register. It has a flat copper collection plate believed to be 17th-century\n[[File:Saint-Thyrse.JPG|thumb|right|Saint Thyrse]]\n*ruins of the Church of St. Andr\u00e9 \u2013 13th century, in ruins since the 18th century (site of Petra Castellana)\n*The 12th-century church of Notre-Dame-du-Plan, a former priory in Castellane\n*Church of St. Sebastian Chasteuil (16th century)\n*Saint-Pons \u2013 16th century, with bell dated 1436, in Robion\n*Saint-Jean in Taloire, may have been built as early as the 13th or 14th century, but the 15th century seems more likely. It was damaged by the earthquake of 1951.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archeoprovence.com/archeo/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=158%3Acastellane&catid=56&Itemid=72|date=December 19, 2010|title=Recherches historiques \u00e9glises et chapelles rurales: Castellane| author=Daniel Thiery|work=Arch\u00e9oprovence}}</ref>\n*St. Pierre in Taulanne\n*Saint-Jean-Baptiste in Villars-Brandis has an exceptional late 15th-century copper [[thurible]] (a type of [[censer]]) with bilevel windows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/palissy_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PM04000060|work=Palissy database|title=Mobilier|trans-title=Furnishings|publisher=minist\u00e8re fran\u00e7ais de la culture}}</ref>\n*Chapelle Sainte-Victoire in a place called Angles: late 19th century at the earliest\n*chapels of Saint-Pons Blaron (ex-Castillon), Saint-Antoine and Notre Dame (ruined) in Eoulx, \n*St. Trophimus, built into the mountain above Petit Robion after a chapel built below was repeatedly damaged by rocks falling onto its roof,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_8=REF&VALUE_8=IA04001142|title=Architecture: chapelle Saint-Trophime|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French}}</ref> has a 17th-century silver chalice and a flat copper 16th-century collection plate, both registered historical items.  \n*St. Stephen, on high ground in Taloire \n*St. John, in Villars\n*the cemetery Notre-Dame-du-Plan includes several funeral chapels\n\n==Military architecture==\n[[File:Castellane_5_PA00080362.jpg|thumb|right|Pentagonal tower]]\nThe outline of the walls of Petra Castellana, the ancient city beneath the current one, is still visible, and in places they reach seven meters in height.<ref name=CIHAM>{{cite web|url=http://ciham.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/petra-castellana-castellane-alpes-haute-provence |title= Petra Castellana (Castellane \u2013 Alpes de Haute-Provence): Campagne de sondages arch\u00e9ologiques du 6 au 17 juin 2016|publisher=Le Centre national de la recherche scientifique|work=CIHAM}}</ref> The walls are thought to date from the 12th century, although a June 2016 archeological excavation sought to date them more precisely.<ref name=CIHAM/> Only one tower survives of the fourteen that originally reinforced these walls: the 14th-century pentagonal keep. This keep, which dominates the town center, is on private property but was declared a historic monument in 1921.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00080362|title=Architecture: Tour pentagonale du 14s sur une hauteur dominant la ville|work=M\u00e9rim\u00e9e database|publisher=minist\u00e8re de la culture fran\u00e7aise|language=French}}</ref>\n[[File:Tour_de_l'Horloge_-_castellane.jpg|thumb|left|Tour de l'Horloge]]\nConstruction on the wall enclosing the lower town began in 1359, with the permission of the [[Count of Provence]], [[Louis I of Naples]]. Traces of this wall are still visible in the square towers on the front of the houses on the square. [[Corbel]]s, which could support defenses ([[brattice]]s or simple [[parapet]]s with [[battlement]]s) are visible on their fa\u00e7ades.\n\nTwo of the original gates in the wall remain:\n*the gate of the Annunciation or of the ''p\u00e9tardiers'', flanked by two towers, high ground in the resistance of 1586;\n* the gate of the clock, also called St. Augustine's gate, set in a square tower. A passage crosses under the tower through an arch. The tower is listed on the register of historic places.\n\nOne of the towers in the Saint-Michel neighborhood has been home to a [[dovecote]] since 1585.\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n|2004|1592\n|2006|1630\n|2007|1604\n|2008|1579\n|2009|1553\n|2010|1537\n|2011|1565\n|2012|1557\n|2013|1549\n|2014|1541\n|2015|1543\n|2016|1547\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n[[File:Castellane Notre Dame du Roc.jpg|center|thumb|Castellane with the \u00c9glise St Denis on \"Le Roc\"]]\n[[File:Int\u00e9rieur_d'une_cuisine_ancienne_en_Haute-Provence,_Maison_Nature_et_Patrimoine_de_Castellane.jpg|center|thumb|An old Proven\u00e7al kitchen, reproduced at a Castellane museum]]\n[[File:France_PACA_04_Castellane_03.jpg|center|thumb|Sacred Heart church]]\n[[File:Map_commune_FR_insee_code_04039.png|center|thumb|Map of Castellane and surrounding communities]]\n\n==International relations==\n\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in France}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\n\nCastellane is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Pescasseroli]], Italy\n\n==See also==\n* [[Route Napol\u00e9on]]\n* [[House of Castellane]]\n*[[Communes of the Alpes-de-Haute-Provence department]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|P\u00e9tardiers}}\n\n*[http://www.insee.fr/en/home/home_page.asp INSEE]\n\n{{Commons category|Castellane}}\n{{Alpes-de-Haute-Provence communes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]]\n[[Category:Subprefectures in France]]\n[[Category:Neolithic sites]]\n[[Category:Gaul]]\n[[Category:War of the Austrian Succession]]\n[[Category:Architectural history]]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Europe]]\n[[Category:History of France by location]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in France]]\n", "name_user": "AndrewCumberland12", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added the correct biographical information on the ruling barons, thier assertion of sovereignty and being a tiny state.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castellane"}
{"title_page": "Unser Stimme", "text_new": "{{Yiddish Journalism}}\n'''''Unsere Schtimme''''' ('Our Voice') was a [[International Jewish Labor Bund|Bundist]] daily [[Yiddish]]-language newspaper published from [[Paris]]. In the early 1960s, it had a circulation of around 3,000. Editors included Jacob Gros, Leon Stern and Abraham Shulman.<ref>[[Socialist International]] (1951- ), and [[Asian Socialist Conference]]. ''Yearbook of the International Socialist Labour Movement''. Volume II 1960-1961 London: Lincolns-Prager International Yearbook Publishing Co., Ltd, 1961. p. 267</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish culture in France]]\n[[Category:Bundism]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Paris]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Yiddish periodicals]]\n[[Category:Yiddish culture in Europe]]\n[[Category:Publications with year of disestablishment missing]]\n[[Category:Publications with year of establishment missing]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Yiddish Journalism}}\n'''''Unsere Schtimme''''' ('Our Voice') was a [[International Jewish Labor Bund|Bundist]] daily [[Yiddish]]-language newspaper published from [[Paris]]. In the early 1960s, it had a circulation of around 3,000. Editors included Jacob Gros, Leon Stern and Abraham Shulman.<ref>[[Socialist International]] (1951- ), and [[Asian Socialist Conference]]. ''Yearbook of the International Socialist Labour Movement''. Volume II 1960-1961 London: Lincolns-Prager International Yearbook Publishing Co., Ltd, 1961. p. 267</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish culture in France]]\n[[Category:Bundism]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Paris]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Yiddish periodicals]]\n[[Category:Yiddish culture i