{"title_page": "Le Temps (Paris)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n[[Image:Soudan fran\u00e7ais-Binger.jpg|thumb|Front page of ''Le Temps'' from March 1890]]\n'''''Le Temps''''' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0259 t\u0251\u0303}}, ''The Times'') was one of [[Paris]]'s most important [[daily newspaper]]s from 25 April 1861 to 30 November 1942.  It was the serious paper of record.\n\nFounded in 1861 by [[Edmund Chojecki]] (writing under the [[pen name]] \"Charles Edmond\") and [[Auguste Nefftzer]], ''Le Temps'' was under Nefftzer's direction for ten years, when [[Adrien H\u00e9brard]] took his place, and for nearly 45 years directed the newspaper with an iron hand until his death in 1914. He was succeeded by his sons \u00c9mile (1914), and Adrien Jr. (1925) and by Louis Mills (1929). Soon after Mills' death in 1931, ''Le Temps'' became a public limited company. Adrien H\u00e9brard and his successors left substantial freedom to the editorial room and the newspaper had the reputation of keeping its journalists for a long time. ''Le Temps'' always remained moderate politically. The early issues of the newspaper reflected Nefftzer's liberal philosophy had considerable trouble achieving readership. He had to frequently turn to friends in [[Alsace]] who were able to help support ''Le Temps'' financially. However, circulation continued to grow, from scarcely 3,000 in 1861, to 11,000 in 1869, 22,000 in 1880, 30,000 in 1884, 35,000 in 1904. During the interwar period it varied between 50,000 and 80,000. Despite this comparatively modest circulation, ''Le Temps'' soon became the most important newspaper of the [[Third French Republic|French Republic]] particularly among the French political and economic elite. The political and diplomatic information and commentaries contained in this quality newspaper, \"serious to the point of boredom\", also carried considerable clout elsewhere in Europe.<ref>C. B\u00e9langer, J. Godechot, etc., ''Histoire g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la presse fran\u00e7aise'', P. U. F., Paris, volume 3, pp. 352\u2013353, 559\u2013561.</ref>\n\nJournalists and correspondents included [[Georges Bruni]], and [[Adolphe Cohn]] in the [[United States]].\n\nThe Paris edition of ''Le Temps'' was suspended by the [[Paris Commune]], and as such, lacks issues from 7 May &ndash; 19 May 1871.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34431794k/date&rk=21459;2|title=Le Temps (Paris. 1861) - 82 Years available - Gallica|website=gallica.bnf.fr|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref> The St. Germain edition, however, ran continuously for 81 years.\n\nOn 28 November 1942, following the German invasion of the Zone Libre, [[Jacques Chastenet]] and [[\u00c9mile Mireaux]], the two co-directors of ''Le Temps'' at the time, jettisoned the newspaper. At [[Charles de Gaulle]]'s request, ''[[Le Monde]]'' was founded on 19 December 1944 to replace ''Le Temps'' as the [[newspaper of record]], borrowing the layout and typeface of ''Le Temps'' for the new newspaper.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yexzGHVggokC|title=The National Daily Press of France|chapter=The Golden Age and the War Years|page=113|first=Clyde|last=Thogmartin|publisher=Summa Publications, Inc|year=1998|isbn=1-883479-20-7}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of French journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34431794k/date ''Le Temps'' digital archives from 1861 to 1940] in [[Gallica]], the digital library of the [[BnF]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Temps}}\n[[Category:1861 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:1942 disestablishments in France]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1942]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:Second French Empire]]\n[[Category:French Third Republic]]\n[[Category:Newspapers of the Vichy regime]]\n[[Category:Contemporary French history]]\n[[Category:Paris Commune]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n[[Image:Soudan fran\u00e7ais-Binger.jpg|thumb|Front page of ''Le Temps'' from March 1890]]\n'''''Le Temps''''' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0259 t\u0251\u0303}}, ''The Times'') was one of [[Paris]]'s most important [[daily newspaper]]s from 25 April 1861 to 30 November 1942.  It was the serious paper of record.\n\nFounded in 1861 by [[Edmund Chojecki]] (writing under the [[pen name]] \"Charles Edmond\") and [[Auguste Nefftzer]], ''Le Temps'' was under Nefftzer's direction for ten years, when [[Adrien H\u00e9brard]] took his place, and for nearly 45 years directed the newspaper with an iron hand until his death in 1914. He was succeeded by his sons \u00c9mile (1914), and Adrien Jr. (1925) and by Louis Mills (1929). Soon after Mills' death in 1931, ''Le Temps'' became a public limited company. Adrien H\u00e9brard and his successors left substantial freedom to the editorial room and the newspaper had the reputation of keeping its journalists for a long time. ''Le Temps'' always remained moderate politically. The early issues of the newspaper reflected Nefftzer's liberal philosophy had considerable trouble achieving readership. He had to frequently turn to friends in [[Alsace]] who were able to help support ''Le Temps'' financially. However, circulation continued to grow, from scarcely 3,000 in 1861, to 11,000 in 1869, 22,000 in 1880, 30,000 in 1884, 35,000 in 1904. During the interwar period it varied between 50,000 and 80,000. Despite this comparatively modest circulation, ''Le Temps'' soon became the most important newspaper of the [[Third French Republic|French Republic]] particularly among the French political and economic elite. The political and diplomatic information and commentaries contained in this quality newspaper, \"serious to the point of boredom\", also carried considerable clout elsewhere in Europe.<ref>C. B\u00e9langer, J. Godechot, etc., ''Histoire g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la presse fran\u00e7aise'', P. U. F., Paris, volume 3, pp. 352\u2013353, 559\u2013561.</ref>\n\nJournalists and correspondents included [[Georges Bruni]], and [[Adolphe Cohn]] in the [[United States]].\n\nThe Paris edition of ''Le Temps'' was suspended by the [[Paris Commune]], and as such, lacks issues from 7 May &ndash; 19 May 1871.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34431794k/date&rk=21459;2|title=Le Temps (Paris. 1861) - 82 Years available - Gallica|website=gallica.bnf.fr|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref> The St. Germain edition, however, ran continuously for 81 years.\n\nOn 28 November 1942, following the German invasion of the Zone Libre, [[Jacques Chastenet]] and [[\u00c9mile Mireaux]], the two co-directors of ''Le Temps'' at the time, jettisoned the newspaper. At [[Charles de Gaulle]]'s request, ''[[Le Monde]]'' was founded on 19 December 1944 to replace ''Le Temps'' as the [[newspaper of record]], borrowing the layout and typeface of ''Le Temps'' for the new newspaper.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yexzGHVggokC|title=The National Daily Press of France|chapter=The Golden Age and the War Years|page=113|first=Clyde|last=Thogmartin|publisher=Summa Publications, Inc|year=1998|isbn=1-883479-20-7}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of French journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34431794k/date ''Le Temps'' digital archives from 1861 to 1940] in [[Gallica]], the digital library of the [[BnF]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Temps}}\n[[Category:1861 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:1942 disestablishments in France]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1942]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:Second French Empire]]\n[[Category:French Third Republic]]\n[[Category:Newspapers of the Vichy regime]]\n[[Category:Contemporary French history]]\n[[Category:Paris Commune]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Temps_(Paris)"}
{"title_page": "Le Soleil (French newspaper)", "text_new": "{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Le Soleil\n| logo                 = \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = Daily news\n| format               = \n| owners               = \n| founder              = [[\u00c9douard Herv\u00e9]] and [[Jean-Jacques Weiss]]\n| publisher            = \n| editor               = \n| foundation           = 1873\n| political            = Monarchist\n| language             = French\n| ceased publication   = June 1915\n| relaunched           =\n| headquarters         = Paris\n| circulation          = \n| sister newspapers    = \n| ISSN                 = \n| oclc                 = \n| website              = \n}}\n[[File:Caf\u00e9 du Croissant.jpg|thumb|240px|Caf\u00e9 du Croissant, by the newspaper's offices]]\n'''''Le Soleil''''' (\"The Sun\") was a French daily newspaper. It was founded in 1873 and run by the journalists [[\u00c9douard Herv\u00e9]] and [[Jean-Jacques Weiss]]. \n''Le Soleil'' was a monarchist daily, more moderate than others, sold for five centimes at the end of the nineteenth and start of the twentieth century. \nIt was located in the rue du Croissant.{{sfn|Le Caf\u00e9 du Croissant 1882}}\nIt was one of two French newspapers that gave the best coverage of international news, along with ''[[Le Temps (1861-1942)|Le Temps]]''.{{sfn|Palmer|1983|p=124}}\n\n==History==\n\nThe newspaper had two founders and editors, [[Jean-Jacques Weiss]] ( 1827 - 1891) and [[\u00c9douard Herv\u00e9]] (1835 - 1899), friends who had worked together on the Orleanist and liberal ''[[Journal de Paris]]''.{{sfn|Meunier|1894|p=226}} \nThey launched the first issue on 28 April 1867.\n\n\u00c9douard Herv\u00e9, a member of the French Academy since 1886, \nformer adviser and friend of the Count of Paris, was the owner-director of ''Le Soleil'' until his death in June 1899.{{sfn|\u00c9douard HERV\u00c9: Academie Francaise}} \nHe said, \"I am Catholic, I even go to Church, but I do not want to serve it in my journal.\"{{sfn|Saint-Martin|1999|p=23}}\nAlways holding liberal opinions in the [[Second French Empire|Second Empire]], \nhe changed to monarchical views with the war of 1870, which soon became apparent from the tone of the articles of his team.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe newspaper hoped to help the merger of legitimists and Orl\u00e9anists.{{sfn|R\u00e9mond|1954|p=263}}\nIt rapidly gaining a readership interested in international affairs, having refused to engage in supporting General [[Georges Boulanger]]. \nIt was one of the papers that sent a reporter to Berlin for the German elections of 1887, while the German Continental Agency only gave out a little information on the subject.{{sfn|Palmer|1983|p=124}}\n\nRenowned for the quality of its articles, ''Le Soleil'' included among its editors the reporter [[F\u00e9lix Dubois]]{{sfn|Saint-Martin|1986|p=92}} (1862 - 1945), [[Hugues Rebell]]{{sfn|Rebell|1994}} (1867 - 1905) and [[Paul B\u00e9zine]] (1861 - 1928), one of the founders of the Association of Young Royalists in 1890, and founder of the anti-Masonic association ''Le Grand Occident de France'', who in 1912 broke with the royalist party.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\nIn 1882 the daily columnist \"Jean de Nivelles\" ([[Charles Canivet]]) worked for the paper.{{sfn|Le Caf\u00e9 du Croissant 1882}}\n\n''Le Soleil'' dropped from 40,000 to 25,000 copies in just one year, between 1898 and 1899, because its readers were baffled by the paper taking up the defense of Captain [[Alfred Dreyfus]], while in general the royalists were against Dreyfus, which caused the departure of the royalist journalist Herv\u00e9 de K\u00e9rohant.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\nDisavowed by the Duke of Orleans, the newspaper passed first to Ambroise Rendu and then to Louis Numa Baragnon ''fils'', who tried in vain to retain its old readers.{{sfn|Bellanger|1969|p=321}}\nAmbroise Rendu was a Paris municipal counsellor. In 1901 he bought ''[[Le Moniteur Universel]]''.\n''Le Soleil'' became a popular daily newspaper, costing only 5 centimes, but displeased many royalists by the tone of its articles. \nThe newspaper closed down during [[World War I]], in June 1915.\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Bellanger|first=Claude|title=Histoire g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la presse fran\u00e7aise: De 1871 \u00e0 1940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nAPsAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA321|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1969|publisher=Presses universitaires de France|page=321}}\n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|\u00c9douard HERV\u00c9: Academie Francaise}} |url=http://www.academie-francaise.fr/les-immortels/edouard-herve?fauteuil=19&election=11-02-1886|title=\u00c9douard HERV\u00c9 |work=Academie Francaise|accessdate=29 April 2013}} \n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|Le Caf\u00e9 du Croissant 1882}}|url=http://www.paris-pittoresque.com/cafes/17.htm |title=LE CAF\u00c9 DU CROISSANT (D'apr\u00e8s Les caf\u00e9s artistiques et litt\u00e9raires de Paris, paru en 1882)|work=Le Paris Pittoresque|accessdate=29 April 2013}} \n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Meunier|first=Georges|title=Les critiques litt\u00e9raires du dix-neuvi\u00e8me si\u00e8cle: (\u00e9tudes et extraits)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P8XLIFbmi5MC&pg=PA226|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1894|publisher=C. Delagrave|page=226}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Palmer|first=Michael B.|title=Des petits jornaux aux grandes agences: naissance du journalisme moderne 1863-1914|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y9QeAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA124|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1983|publisher=Aubier|isbn=978-2-7007-0346-7|page=124}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rebell|first=Hugues|title=De mon balcon: recueil de chroniques et d'articles in\u00e9dits, extraits des journaux, La Cocarde & Le Soleil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lc1cAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1994|publisher=Libr. La Vouivre|isbn=978-2-9506621-1-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=R\u00e9mond|first=Ren\u00e9|title=La droite en France de 1815 \u00e0 nos jours: continuit\u00e9 et diversit\u00e9 d'une tradition politique|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Htk7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA263|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1954|publisher=Aubier|page=263}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |url=http://www.medias19.org/docannexe/file/11084/l_academie_des_sciences_d_outre_mer.pdf|last=Saint-Martin |first=Yves T.|publisher=L'Acad\u00e9mie des sciences d'outre-mer | title=Hommes et Destins Volume 7: Maghreb-Machrek|year=1986|chapter=F\u00e9lix Dubois (1862-1945) | pages=92\u201399 | place=Paris | isbn=978-2-900098-13-4|accessdate=27 April 2013}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Saint-Martin|first=Yves-Jean|title=F\u00e9lix Dubois: 1862-1945 : grand reporter et explorateur, de Panama \u00e0 Tamanrasset|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q82ChVxvq2AC&pg=PA23|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1999|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|isbn=978-2-7384-8715-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soleil}}\n[[Category:1873 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:French penny papers]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1915]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Le Soleil\n| logo                 = \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = Daily news\n| format               = \n| owners               = \n| founder              = [[\u00c9douard Herv\u00e9]] and [[Jean-Jacques Weiss]]\n| publisher            = \n| editor               = \n| foundation           = 1873\n| political            = Monarchist\n| language             = French\n| ceased publication   = June 1915\n| relaunched           =\n| headquarters         = Paris\n| circulation     