399 | place=Paris | isbn=978-2-900098-13-4|accessdate=27 April 2013}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Saint-Martin|first=Yves-Jean|title=F\u00e9lix Dubois: 1862-1945 : grand reporter et explorateur, de Panama \u00e0 Tamanrasset|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q82ChVxvq2AC&pg=PA23|accessdate=29 April 2013|year=1999|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|isbn=978-2-7384-8715-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soleil}}\n[[Category:1873 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:French penny papers]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1915]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Soleil_(French_newspaper)"}
{"title_page": "Magnetic anomaly", "text_new": "{{Details|Magnetic striping}}\n[[File:Global Map of Martian Magnetic Anomalies PIA02059.jpg|thumb|Satellite measurements of the radial magnetic field on Mars.]]\nIn [[geophysics]], a '''magnetic anomaly''' is a local variation in the [[Earth's magnetic field]] resulting from variations in the chemistry or magnetism of the rocks. Mapping of variation over an area is valuable in detecting structures obscured by overlying material. The magnetic variation in successive bands of ocean floor parallel with [[mid-ocean ridge]]s is important evidence supporting the theory of [[seafloor spreading]], central to [[plate tectonics]].\n\n==Measurement==\nMagnetic anomalies are generally  a small fraction of the magnetic field. The total field ranges from 25,000 to 65,000&nbsp;[[nanotesla]]s (nT).<ref name=NGDC>{{cite web |url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/geomag/faqgeom.shtml |title=Geomagnetism Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=National Geophysical Data Center |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> To measure anomalies, [[magnetometer]]s need a sensitivity of 10 nT or less. There are three main types of magnetometer used to measure magnetic anomalies:<ref name=Mussett>{{cite book |last1=Mussett |first1=Alan E. |last2=Khan |first2=M. Aftab |chapter=11. Magnetic surveying |title=Looking into the earth: an introduction to geological geophysics |year=2000 |publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-78085-3 |pages=162\u2013180 |edition=1. publ., repr.}}</ref>{{rp|162\u2013164}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|77\u201379}}\n\n# The [[fluxgate magnetometer]] was developed during World War II to detect submarines.<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|75}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Murray |first=Raymond C. |title=Evidence from the earth: forensic geology and criminal investigation |date=2004 |publisher=Mountain press publ. company |location=Missoula (Mont.) |isbn=978-0-87842-498-6 |pages=162\u2013163}}</ref> It measures the component along a particular axis of the sensor, so it needs to be oriented. On land, it is often oriented vertically, while in aircraft, ships and satellites it is usually oriented so the axis is in the direction of the field. It measures the magnetic field continuously, but drifts over time. One way to correct for drift is to take repeated measurements at the same place during the survey.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|163\u2013165}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|75\u201377}}\n# The [[proton precession magnetometer]] measures the strength of the field but not its direction, so it does not need to be oriented. Each measurement takes a second or more. It is used in most ground surveys except for boreholes and high-resolution gradiometer surveys.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|163\u2013165}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|77\u201378}}\n# [[Magnetometer#Optical_magnetometry|Optically pumped magnetometer]]s, which use alkali gases (most commonly [[rubidium]] and [[caesium]]) have high sample rates and sensitivities of 0.001&nbsp;nT or less, but are more expensive than the other types of magnetometers. They are used on satellites and in most [[aeromagnetic survey]]s.<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|78\u201379}}\n\n==Data acquisition==\n\n===Ground-based===\nIn ground-based surveys, measurements are made at a series of stations, typically 15 to 60&nbsp;m apart. Usually a proton precession magnetometer is used and it is often mounted on a pole. Raising the magnetometer reduces the influence of small ferrous objects that were discarded by humans. To further reduce unwanted signals, they do not carry objects such as keys, knives or compasses. In addition, objects such as motor vehicles, railway lines, and barbed wire fences are avoided. If some such contaminant is overlooked, it often shows up as a sharp spike in the anomaly, so such features are treated with suspicion. The main application for ground-based surveys is detailed search for minerals.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|163}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|83&ndash;84}}\n\n[[File:Novatem CGJDD.jpg|thumb]]\n===Aeromagnetic===\n{{Main|Aeromagnetic survey}}\n\nAirborne magnetic surveys are often used in oil surveys to provide preliminary information for seismic surveys. In some countries such as Canada, government agencies have made systematic surveys of large areas. The survey generally involves making a series of parallel runs at a constant height and intervals of anywhere from a hundred meters to several kilometers. These are crossed by occasional tie lines, perpendicular to the main survey, to check for errors. The plane is a source of magnetism, so sensors are either mounted on a boom (as in the figure) or towed behind on a cable. Aeromagnetic surveys have a lower spatial resolution of ground surveys, but this can be an advantage for a regional survey of deeper rocks.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|166}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|81&ndash;83}}\n\n===Shipborne===\nIn shipborne surveys, a magnetometer is towed a few hundred meters behind a ship in a device called a ''fish''. The sensor is kept at a constant depth of about 15&nbsp;m. Otherwise, the procedure is similar to that used in aeromagnetic surveys.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|83}}\n\n===Spacecraft===\nThe [[Sputnik 3]] spacecraft in 1958 was the first to carry a magnetometer.<ref name=\"Dicati\">{{cite book|last1=Dicati|first1=Renato|title=Stamping the Earth from Space|date=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319207568}}</ref>{{rp|155}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Purucker|first=Michael E.|last2=Whaler|first2=Kathryn A. |chapter=6. Crustal magnetism |series=Treatise on Geophysics|volume=5|editor-last=Kono|editor-first=M.|title=Geomagnetism|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-444-52748-6|page=195&ndash;236|url=http://core2.gsfc.nasa.gov/research/purucker/chapter6_draft_v2.8_wfigs.pdf}}</ref> In the fall of 1979, [[Magsat]] was launched and jointly operated by [[NASA]] and [[USGS]] until the spring of 1980. It had a [[caesium]] vapor scalar magnetometer and a fluxgate vector magnetometer.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Langel|first=Robert|author2=Ousley, Gilbert |author3=Berbert, John |author4=Murphy, James |author5= Settle, Mark |title=The MAGSAT mission|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|date=April 1982|volume=9|issue=4|pages=243\u2013245|doi=10.1029/GL009i004p00243}}</ref> [[CHAMP (satellite)|CHAMP]], a German satellite, made precise gravity and magnetic measurements from 2001 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=The CHAMP mission|url=http://op.gfz-potsdam.de/champ/|publisher=GFZ German Research Centre for Geosciences|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Reigber|editor-first=Christoph|title=Earth observation with CHAMP : results from three years in orbit|date=2005|publisher=Springer|location=Berlin|isbn=9783540228042|edition=1st}}</ref>  A Danish satellite, [[\u00d8rsted (satellite)|\u00d8rsted]], was launched in 1999 and is still in operation, while the [[Swarm (spacecraft)|Swarm]] mission of the [[European Space Agency]] involves a \"constellation\" of three satellites that were launched in November, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staunting|first=Peter|title=The \u00d8rsted Satellite Project|url=http://web.dmi.dk/projects/oersted/oerstedresults.pdf|publisher=Danish Meteorological Institute|date=1 January 2008|accessdate=20 March 2014}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Swarm (Geomagnetic LEO Constellation)|url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/s/swarm|work=eoPortal Directory|publisher=European Space Agency|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Olsen|first=Nils|author2=Stavros Kotsiaros|title=Magnetic Satellite Missions and Data|journal=IAGA Special Sopron Book Series|year=2011|volume=5|pages=27&ndash;44|doi=10.1007/978-90-481-9858-0-2}}</ref>\n\n==Data reduction==\nThere are two main corrections that are needed for magnetic measurements. The first is remove short-term variations in the field from external sources. There are ''diurnal variations'' that have a period of 24&nbsp;hours and magnitudes of up to 30&nbsp;nT, probably from the action of the [[solar wind]] on the [[ionosphere]].<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|72}} In addition, [[magnetic storm]]s can have peak magnitudes of 1000&nbsp;nT and can last for several days. Their contribution can be measured by returning to a base station repeatedly or by having another magnetometer that periodically measures the field at a fixed location.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}\n\nThe anomaly is the local contribution to the magnetic field, so the main geomagnetic field must be subtracted from it. Usually the [[International Geomagnetic Reference Field]] is used for this purpose. This is a large-scale, time-averaged mathematical model of the Earth's field based on measurements from satellites, magnetic observatories and other surveys.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}\n\nSome corrections that are needed for [[gravity anomaly|gravity anomalies]] are less important for magnetic anomalies. For example, the vertical gradient of the magnetic field is 0.03&nbsp;nT/m or less, so an elevation correction is generally not needed.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}\n\n==Interpretation==\n===Theoretical background===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" border=\"0\" style=\"text-align: right;\" align=\"right\"\n|+ Magnetic susceptibilities of common rocks and minerals<ref name=Telford>{{cite book|last=Telford|first=W. M.|author2=L. P. Geldart |author3=R. E. Sheriff  |chapter = 3. Magnetic methods |title=Applied geophysics|date=2001|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0521339383|pages=62&ndash;135|edition=2nd, repr.}}</ref>{{rp|74}}\n|-\n! Type !! Susceptibility (<math>\\times 10^{-3}</math> SI)\n|-\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Sedimentary'' \n|-\n| [[Limestones]] || 0-3\n|-\n| [[Sandstones]] || 0-20\n|-\n| [[Shales]] || 0.01-15\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Igneous'' \n|-\n| [[Basalt]] || 0.2-175\n|-\n| [[Gabbro]] || 1-90\n|-\n| [[Granite]] || 0-50\n|-\n| [[Rhyolite]] || 0.2-35\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Metamorphic'' \n|-\n| [[Gneiss]] || 0.1-25\n|-\n| [[Serpentine group|Serpentine]] || 3-17\n|-\n| [[Slate]] || 0-35\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Minerals'' \n|-\n| [[Graphite]] || 0.1\n|-\n| [[Quartz]] || -0.01\n|-\n| [[Coal]] || 0.02\n|-\n| [[Clays]] || 0.2\n|-\n| [[Pyrrhotite]] || 1-6000\n|-\n| [[Magnetite]] || 1200-19200\n|}\nThe magnetization in the surveyed rock is a vector sum of induced and [[Remanence|remanent magnetization]]:\n:<math> \\mathbf{M} = \\mathbf{M}_\\text{i} + \\mathbf{M}_\\text{r}.</math>\nThe induced magnetization of many minerals is the product of the ambient magnetic field and their [[magnetic susceptibility]] {{math|&chi;}}:\n:<math> \\mathbf{M}_\\text{i} = \\chi \\mathbf{H}. </math>\nSome susceptibilities are given in the table.\n\nMinerals that are [[diamagnetism|diamagnetic]] or [[paramagnetism|paramagnetic]] only have an induced magnetization. [[Ferromagnetism|Ferromagnetic]] minerals such as [[magnetite]] also can carry a remanent magnetization or remanence. This remanence can last for millions of years, so it may be in a completely different direction from the present Earth's field. If a remanence is present, it is difficult to separate from the induced magnetization unless samples of the rock are measured. The ratio of the magnitudes, {{math|''Q'' {{=}} ''M''<sub>r</sub>/''M''<sub>i</sub>}}, is called the [[Koenigsberger ratio]].<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|172&ndash;173}}<ref name=Clark>{{cite journal|last=Clark|first=D. A.|title=Magnetic petrophysics and magnetic petrology: aids to geological interpretation of magnetic surveys|journal=AGSO Journal of Australian Geology & Geophysics|date=1997|volume=17|issue=2|pages=83&ndash;103|url=http://www.ga.gov.au/image_cache/GA1691.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320040347/http://www.ga.gov.au/image_cache/GA1691.pdf|archivedate=20 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Magnetic anomaly modeling===\n\nInterpretation of magnetic anomalies is usually done by matching observed and modeled values. Talwani and Heirtzler (1964) were first to examine a nonmagnetic space containing a uniformly magnetized two\u2010dimensional structure approximated by a polygonal prism and to suggest a numerical and computational technique of the forward modeling.<ref name=Talwani>{{cite book|last=Talwani|first= M.|author2=J. R. Heirtzler |title=Computation of magnetic anomalies caused by two dimensional structures of arbitrary shape|date=1964|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=v_niKhUAAAAJ&hl=en&oi=sra}}</ref>\n\nThis algorithm was re-derived from the first principles and some of the omissions were corrected.<ref name=Kravchinsky>{{cite book|last=Kravchinsky|first=V. A.|author2=D. Hnatyshin |author3=B. Lysak  |author4=W. Alemie  |title=Computation of magnetic anomalies caused by two dimensional structures of arbitrary shape: derivation and Matlab implementation|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|date=2019|volume=46|issue=13|pages=7345&ndash;7351|url=https://doi.org/10.1029/2019GL082767}}</ref> The new algorithm treats both induced and remnant magnetizations as vectors.\n\n==Applications==\n\n===Ocean floor stripes===\n[[File:Magnetic anomalies off west coast of North America.gif|thumb|upright|Magnetic anomalies around the Juan de Fuca and Gorda Ridges, off the west coast of North America, color-coded by age.]]\nMagnetic surveys over the oceans have revealed a characteristic pattern of anomalies around mid-ocean ridges. They involve a series of positive and negative anomalies in the intensity of the magnetic field, forming stripes running parallel to each ridge. They are often symmetric about the axis of the ridge. The stripes are generally tens of kilometers wide, and the anomalies are a few hundred nanoteslas. The source of these anomalies is primarily permanent magnetization carried by titanomagnetite minerals in [[basalt]] and [[gabbro]]s. They are magnetized when ocean crust is formed at the ridge. As [[magma]] rises to the surface and cools, the rock acquires a [[thermoremanent magnetization]] in the direction of the field. Then the rock is carried away from the ridge by the motions of the [[tectonic plate]]s. Every few hundred thousand years, the direction of the magnetic field [[Geomagnetic reversal|reverses]]. Thus, the pattern of stripes is a global phenomenon and can be used to calculate the velocity of [[seafloor spreading]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Merrill |first2=Michael W. |last2=McElhinny |first3=Phillip L. |last3=McFadden|first=Ronald T.|title=The magnetic field of the earth : paleomagnetism, the core, and the deep mantle|date=1996|publisher=Acad. Press|location=San Diego|isbn=0124912451|pages=172&ndash;185}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Turcotte|first=Donald L.|title=Geodynamics|date=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107006539|pages=34&ndash;39}}</ref>\n\n==In fiction==\nIn the ''[[Space Odyssey]]'' series by [[Arthur C. Clarke]], a series of [[Monolith (Space Odyssey)|monoliths]] are left by extraterrestrials for humans to find them. One near the crater [[Tycho (crater)|Tycho]] is found by its unnaturally powerful magnetic field and named ''Tycho Magnetic Anomaly 1'' (TMA-1).<ref>{{cite book|last=Nelson|first=Thomas Allen|title=Kubrick : inside a film artist's maze|date=2000|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=9780253213907|page=107|edition=New and expanded}}</ref>  One orbiting Jupiter is named TMA-2, and one in the [[Olduvai Gorge]] is found in 2513 and retroactively named TMA-0 because it was first encountered by primitive humans.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Geomagnetism}}\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Bangui magnetic anomaly]]\n*[[Geomagnetic reversal]]\n*[[Kursk Magnetic Anomaly]]\n*[[Magnetic anomaly detector]]\n*[[South Atlantic Anomaly]]\n*[[Temagami Magnetic Anomaly]]\n*[[World Digital Magnetic Anomaly Map]] (WDMAM)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Constable |first=Catherine G.|first2=Steven C. |last2=Constable |chapter = Satellite Magnetic Field Measurements: Applications in Studying the Deep Earth|pages=147&ndash;159|editor-last=Sparks|editor-first=Robert Stephen John|editor2-first=Christopher John |editor2-last=Hawkesworth |title=The state of the planet frontiers and challenges in geophysics|date=2004|publisher=American Geophysical Union|location=Washington, DC|isbn=9781118666012}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hinze|first=William J.|first2=Ralph R.B. von |last2=Frese |first3=Afif H. |last3=Saad |title=Gravity and magnetic exploration : principles, practices, and applications|date=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=9780521871013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hinze|first=R. A. Langel, W. J.|title=The magnetic field of the earth's lithosphere : the satellite perspective|date=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, U.K.|isbn=978-0521189644|edition=1st pap.}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kearey|first=Philip|first2=Michael |last2=Brooks |first3=Ian |last3=Hill |chapter=7. Magnetic surveying|title=An Introduction to Geophysical Exploration|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9781118698938}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Maus|first=S.|last2=Barckhausen |first2=U.|last3= Berkenbosch |first3=H.|last4= Bournas|first4=N.|last5= Brozena |first5=J.|last6= Childers |first6=V.|last7= Dostaler |first7=F.|last8= Fairhead |first8=J. D.|last9= Finn |first9=C.|last10= von Frese |first10=R. R. B.|last11= Gaina |first11=C.|last12= Golynsky |first12=S.|last13= Kucks |first13=R.|last14= L\u00fchr |first14=H.|last15= Milligan |first15=P.|last16= Mogren |first16=S.|last17= M\u00fcller |first17=R. D.|last18= Olesen |first18=O.|last19= Pilkington |first19=M.|last20= Saltus |first20=R.|last21= Schreckenberger |first21=B.|last22= Th\u00e9bault |first22=E.|last23= Caratori Tontini |first23=F.|displayauthors=9|title=EMAG2: A 2-arc min resolution Earth Magnetic Anomaly Grid compiled from satellite, airborne, and marine magnetic measurements|journal=Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems|date=August 2009|volume=10|issue=8|pages=|doi=10.1029/2009GC002471}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://geomag.org/info/lithosphere.html Magnetic field of the lithosphere] (CIRES)\n*[http://mrdata.usgs.gov/magnetic/ Magnetic anomaly maps and data for North America] (USGS)\n*[http://projects.gtk.fi/WDMAM/index.html World Digital Magnetic Anomaly Map: info]\n*[http://projects.gtk.fi/export/sites/projects/WDMAM/general/WDMAM_1.03_2007_Edition_1_250_000_000.pdf Magnetic anomaly map of the world]\n*[http://sservi.nasa.gov/articles/asteroids-may-have-delivered-magnetic-material-to-the-moon/ Asteroids may have delivered magnetic material to the Moon]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magnetic Anomaly}}\n[[Category:Magnetic anomalies| ]]\n[[Category:Geomagnetism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Details|Magnetic striping}}\n[[File:Global Map of Martian Magnetic Anomalies PIA02059.jpg|thumb|Satellite measurements of the radial magnetic field on Mars.]]\nIn [[geophysics]], a '''magnetic anomaly''' is a local variation in the [[Earth's magnetic field]] resulting from variations in the chemistry or magnetism of the rocks. Mapping of variation over an area is valuable in detecting structures obscured by overlying material. The magnetic variation in successive bands of ocean floor parallel with [[mid-ocean ridge]]s is important evidence supporting the theory of [[seafloor spreading]], central to [[plate tectonics]].\n\n==Measurement==\nMagnetic anomalies are generally  a small fraction of the magnetic field. The total field ranges from 25,000 to 65,000&nbsp;[[nanotesla]]s (nT).<ref name=NGDC>{{cite web |url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/geomag/faqgeom.shtml |title=Geomagnetism Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=National Geophysical Data Center |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> To measure anomalies, [[magnetometer]]s need a sensitivity of 10 nT or less. There are three main types of magnetometer used to measure magnetic anomalies:<ref name=Mussett>{{cite book |last1=Mussett |first1=Alan E. |last2=Khan |first2=M. Aftab |chapter=11. Magnetic surveying |title=Looking into the earth: an introduction to geological geophysics |year=2000 |publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-78085-3 |pages=162\u2013180 |edition=1. publ., repr.}}</ref>{{rp|162\u2013164}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|77\u201379}}\n\n# The [[fluxgate magnetometer]] was developed during World War II to detect submarines.<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|75}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Murray |first=Raymond C. |title=Evidence from the earth: forensic geology and criminal investigation |date=2004 |publisher=Mountain press publ. company |location=Missoula (Mont.) |isbn=978-0-87842-498-6 |pages=162\u2013163}}</ref> It measures the component along a particular axis of the sensor, so it needs to be oriented. On land, it is often oriented vertically, while in aircraft, ships and satellites it is usually oriented so the axis is in the direction of the field. It measures the magnetic field continuously, but drifts over time. One way to correct for drift is to take repeated measurements at the same place during the survey.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|163\u2013165}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|75\u201377}}\n# The [[proton precession magnetometer]] measures the strength of the field but not its direction, so it does not need to be oriented. Each measurement takes a second or more. It is used in most ground surveys except for boreholes and high-resolution gradiometer surveys.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|163\u2013165}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|77\u201378}}\n# [[Magnetometer#Optical_magnetometry|Optically pumped magnetometer]]s, which use alkali gases (most commonly [[rubidium]] and [[caesium]]) have high sample rates and sensitivities of 0.001&nbsp;nT or less, but are more expensive than the other types of magnetometers. They are used on satellites and in most [[aeromagnetic survey]]s.<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|78\u201379}}\n\n==Data acquisition==\n\n===Ground-based===\nIn ground-based surveys, measurements are made at a series of stations, typically 15 to 60&nbsp;m apart. Usually a proton precession magnetometer is used and it is often mounted on a pole. Raising the magnetometer reduces the influence of small ferrous objects that were discarded by humans. To further reduce unwanted signals, they do not carry objects such as keys, knives or compasses. In addition, objects such as motor vehicles, railway lines, and barbed wire fences are avoided. If some such contaminant is overlooked, it often shows up as a sharp spike in the anomaly, so such features are treated with suspicion. The main application for ground-based surveys is detailed search for minerals.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|163}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|83&ndash;84}}\n\n[[File:Novatem CGJDD.jpg|thumb]]\n===Aeromagnetic===\n{{Main|Aeromagnetic survey}}\n\nAirborne magnetic surveys are often used in oil surveys to provide preliminary information for seismic surveys. In some countries such as Canada, government agencies have made systematic surveys of large areas. The survey generally involves making a series of parallel runs at a constant height and intervals of anywhere from a hundred meters to several kilometers. These are crossed by occasional tie lines, perpendicular to the main survey, to check for errors. The plane is a source of magnetism, so sensors are either mounted on a boom (as in the figure) or towed behind on a cable. Aeromagnetic surveys have a lower spatial resolution of ground surveys, but this can be an advantage for a regional survey of deeper rocks.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|166}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|81&ndash;83}}\n\n===Shipborne===\nIn shipborne surveys, a magnetometer is towed a few hundred meters behind a ship in a device called a ''fish''. The sensor is kept at a constant depth of about 15&nbsp;m. Otherwise, the procedure is similar to that used in aeromagnetic surveys.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|83}}\n\n===Spacecraft===\nThe [[Sputnik 3]] spacecraft in 1958 was the first to carry a magnetometer.<ref name=\"Dicati\">{{cite book|last1=Dicati|first1=Renato|title=Stamping the Earth from Space|date=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319207568}}</ref>{{rp|155}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Purucker|first=Michael E.|last2=Whaler|first2=Kathryn A. |chapter=6. Crustal magnetism |series=Treatise on Geophysics|volume=5|editor-last=Kono|editor-first=M.|title=Geomagnetism|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-444-52748-6|page=195&ndash;236|url=http://core2.gsfc.nasa.gov/research/purucker/chapter6_draft_v2.8_wfigs.pdf}}</ref> In the fall of 1979, [[Magsat]] was launched and jointly operated by [[NASA]] and [[USGS]] until the spring of 1980. It had a [[caesium]] vapor scalar magnetometer and a fluxgate vector magnetometer.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Langel|first=Robert|author2=Ousley, Gilbert |author3=Berbert, John |author4=Murphy, James |author5= Settle, Mark |title=The MAGSAT mission|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|date=April 1982|volume=9|issue=4|pages=243\u2013245|doi=10.1029/GL009i004p00243}}</ref> [[CHAMP (satellite)|CHAMP]], a German satellite, made precise gravity and magnetic measurements from 2001 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=The CHAMP mission|url=http://op.gfz-potsdam.de/champ/|publisher=GFZ German Research Centre for Geosciences|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Reigber|editor-first=Christoph|title=Earth observation with CHAMP : results from three years in orbit|date=2005|publisher=Springer|location=Berlin|isbn=9783540228042|edition=1st}}</ref>  A Danish satellite, [[\u00d8rsted (satellite)|\u00d8rsted]], was launched in 1999 and is still in operation, while the [[Swarm (spacecraft)|Swarm]] mission of the [[European Space Agency]] involves a \"constellation\" of three satellites that were launched in November, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staunting|first=Peter|title=The \u00d8rsted Satellite Project|url=http://web.dmi.dk/projects/oersted/oerstedresults.pdf|publisher=Danish Meteorological Institute|date=1 January 2008|accessdate=20 March 2014}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Swarm (Geomagnetic LEO Constellation)|url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/s/swarm|work=eoPortal Directory|publisher=European Space Agency|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Olsen|first=Nils|author2=Stavros Kotsiaros|title=Magnetic Satellite Missions and Data|journal=IAGA Special Sopron Book Series|year=2011|volume=5|pages=27&ndash;44|doi=10.1007/978-90-481-9858-0-2}}</ref>\n\n==Data reduction==\nThere are two main corrections that are needed for magnetic measurements. The first is remove short-term variations in the field from external sources. There are ''diurnal variations'' that have a period of 24&nbsp;hours and magnitudes of up to 30&nbsp;nT, probably from the action of the [[solar wind]] on the [[ionosphere]].<ref name=Telford/>{{rp|72}} In addition, [[magnetic storm]]s can have peak magnitudes of 1000&nbsp;nT and can last for several days. Their contribution can be measured by returning to a base station repeatedly or by having another magnetometer that periodically measures the field at a fixed location.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}\n\nThe anomaly is the local contribution to the magnetic field, so the main geomagnetic field must be subtracted from it. Usually the [[International Geomagnetic Reference Field]] is used for this purpose. This is a large-scale, time-averaged mathematical model of the Earth's field based on measurements from satellites, magnetic observatories and other surveys.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}\n\nSome corrections that are needed for [[gravity anomaly|gravity anomalies]] are less important for magnetic anomalies. For example, the vertical gradient of the magnetic field is 0.03&nbsp;nT/m or less, so an elevation correction is generally not needed.<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|167}}\n\n==Interpretation==\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" border=\"0\" style=\"text-align: right;\" align=\"right\"\n|+ Magnetic susceptibilities of common rocks and minerals<ref name=Telford>{{cite book|last=Telford|first=W. M.|author2=L. P. Geldart |author3=R. E. Sheriff  |chapter = 3. Magnetic methods |title=Applied geophysics|date=2001|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0521339383|pages=62&ndash;135|edition=2nd, repr.}}</ref>{{rp|74}}\n|-\n! Type !! Susceptibility (<math>\\times 10^{-3}</math> SI)\n|-\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Sedimentary'' \n|-\n| [[Limestones]] || 0-3\n|-\n| [[Sandstones]] || 0-20\n|-\n| [[Shales]] || 0.01-15\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Igneous'' \n|-\n| [[Basalt]] || 0.2-175\n|-\n| [[Gabbro]] || 1-90\n|-\n| [[Granite]] || 0-50\n|-\n| [[Rhyolite]] || 0.2-35\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Metamorphic'' \n|-\n| [[Gneiss]] || 0.1-25\n|-\n| [[Serpentine group|Serpentine]] || 3-17\n|-\n| [[Slate]] || 0-35\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | ''Minerals'' \n|-\n| [[Graphite]] || 0.1\n|-\n| [[Quartz]] || -0.01\n|-\n| [[Coal]] || 0.02\n|-\n| [[Clays]] || 0.2\n|-\n| [[Pyrrhotite]] || 1-6000\n|-\n| [[Magnetite]] || 1200-19200\n|}\nThe magnetization in the surveyed rock is a vector sum of induced and [[Remanence|remanent magnetization]]:\n:<math> \\mathbf{M} = \\mathbf{M}_\\text{i} + \\mathbf{M}_\\text{r}.</math>\nThe induced magnetization of many minerals is the product of the ambient magnetic field and their [[magnetic susceptibility]] {{math|&chi;}}:\n:<math> \\mathbf{M}_\\text{i} = \\chi \\mathbf{H}. </math>\nSome susceptibilities are given in the table.\n\nMinerals that are [[diamagnetism|diamagnetic]] or [[paramagnetism|paramagnetic]] only have an induced magnetization. [[Ferromagnetism|Ferromagnetic]] minerals such as [[magnetite]] also can carry a remanent magnetization or remanence. This remanence can last for millions of years, so it may be in a completely different direction from the present Earth's field. If a remanence is present, it is difficult to separate from the induced magnetization unless samples of the rock are measured. The ratio of the magnitudes, {{math|''Q'' {{=}} ''M''<sub>r</sub>/''M''<sub>i</sub>}}, is called the [[Koenigsberger ratio]].<ref name=Mussett/>{{rp|172&ndash;173}}<ref name=Clark>{{cite journal|last=Clark|first=D. A.|title=Magnetic petrophysics and magnetic petrology: aids to geological interpretation of magnetic surveys|journal=AGSO Journal of Australian Geology & Geophysics|date=1997|volume=17|issue=2|pages=83&ndash;103|url=http://www.ga.gov.au/image_cache/GA1691.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320040347/http://www.ga.gov.au/image_cache/GA1691.pdf|archivedate=20 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n\n===Ocean floor stripes===\n[[File:Magnetic anomalies off west coast of North America.gif|thumb|upright|Magnetic anomalies around the Juan de Fuca and Gorda Ridges, off the west coast of North America, color-coded by age.]]\nMagnetic surveys over the oceans have revealed a characteristic pattern of anomalies around mid-ocean ridges. They involve a series of positive and negative anomalies in the intensity of the magnetic field, forming stripes running parallel to each ridge. They are often symmetric about the axis of the ridge. The stripes are generally tens of kilometers wide, and the anomalies are a few hundred nanoteslas. The source of these anomalies is primarily permanent magnetization carried by titanomagnetite minerals in [[basalt]] and [[gabbro]]s. They are magnetized when ocean crust is formed at the ridge. As [[magma]] rises to the surface and cools, the rock acquires a [[thermoremanent magnetization]] in the direction of the field. Then the rock is carried away from the ridge by the motions of the [[tectonic plate]]s. Every few hundred thousand years, the direction of the magnetic field [[Geomagnetic reversal|reverses]]. Thus, the pattern of stripes is a global phenomenon and can be used to calculate the velocity of [[seafloor spreading]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Merrill |first2=Michael W. |last2=McElhinny |first3=Phillip L. |last3=McFadden|first=Ronald T.|title=The magnetic field of the earth : paleomagnetism, the core, and the deep mantle|date=1996|publisher=Acad. Press|location=San Diego|isbn=0124912451|pages=172&ndash;185}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Turcotte|first=Donald L.|title=Geodynamics|date=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107006539|pages=34&ndash;39}}</ref>\n\n==In fiction==\nIn the ''[[Space Odyssey]]'' series by [[Arthur C. Clarke]], a series of [[Monolith (Space Odyssey)|monoliths]] are left by extraterrestrials for humans to find them. One near the crater [[Tycho (crater)|Tycho]] is found by its unnaturally powerful magnetic field and named ''Tycho Magnetic Anomaly 1'' (TMA-1).<ref>{{cite book|last=Nelson|first=Thomas Allen|title=Kubrick : inside a film artist's maze|date=2000|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=9780253213907|page=107|edition=New and expanded}}</ref>  One orbiting Jupiter is named TMA-2, and one in the [[Olduvai Gorge]] is found in 2513 and retroactively named TMA-0 because it was first encountered by primitive humans.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Geomagnetism}}\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Bangui magnetic anomaly]]\n*[[Geomagnetic reversal]]\n*[[Kursk Magnetic Anomaly]]\n*[[Magnetic anomaly detector]]\n*[[South Atlantic Anomaly]]\n*[[Temagami Magnetic Anomaly]]\n*[[World Digital Magnetic Anomaly Map]] (WDMAM)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Constable |first=Catherine G.|first2=Steven C. |last2=Constable |chapter = Satellite Magnetic Field Measurements: Applications in Studying the Deep Earth|pages=147&ndash;159|editor-last=Sparks|editor-first=Robert Stephen John|editor2-first=Christopher John |editor2-last=Hawkesworth |title=The state of the planet frontiers and challenges in geophysics|date=2004|publisher=American Geophysical Union|location=Washington, DC|isbn=9781118666012}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hinze|first=William J.|first2=Ralph R.B. von |last2=Frese |first3=Afif H. |last3=Saad |title=Gravity and magnetic exploration : principles, practices, and applications|date=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=9780521871013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hinze|first=R. A. Langel, W. J.|title=The magnetic field of the earth's lithosphere : the satellite perspective|date=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, U.K.|isbn=978-0521189644|edition=1st pap.}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kearey|first=Philip|first2=Michael |last2=Brooks |first3=Ian |last3=Hill |chapter=7. Magnetic surveying|title=An Introduction to Geophysical Exploration|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9781118698938}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Maus|first=S.|last2=Barckhausen |first2=U.|last3= Berkenbosch |first3=H.|last4= Bournas|first4=N.|last5= Brozena |first5=J.|last6= Childers |first6=V.|last7= Dostaler |first7=F.|last8= Fairhead |first8=J. D.|last9= Finn |first9=C.|last10= von Frese |first10=R. R. B.|last11= Gaina |first11=C.|last12= Golynsky |first12=S.|last13= Kucks |first13=R.|last14= L\u00fchr |first14=H.|last15= Milligan |first15=P.|last16= Mogren |first16=S.|last17= M\u00fcller |first17=R. D.|last18= Olesen |first18=O.|last19= Pilkington |first19=M.|last20= Saltus |first20=R.|last21= Schreckenberger |first21=B.|last22= Th\u00e9bault |first22=E.|last23= Caratori Tontini |first23=F.|displayauthors=9|title=EMAG2: A 2-arc min resolution Earth Magnetic Anomaly Grid compiled from satellite, airborne, and marine magnetic measurements|journal=Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems|date=August 2009|volume=10|issue=8|pages=|doi=10.1029/2009GC002471}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://geomag.org/info/lithosphere.html Magnetic field of the lithosphere] (CIRES)\n*[http://mrdata.usgs.gov/magnetic/ Magnetic anomaly maps and data for North America] (USGS)\n*[http://projects.gtk.fi/WDMAM/index.html World Digital Magnetic Anomaly Map: info]\n*[http://projects.gtk.fi/export/sites/projects/WDMAM/general/WDMAM_1.03_2007_Edition_1_250_000_000.pdf Magnetic anomaly map of the world]\n*[http://sservi.nasa.gov/articles/asteroids-may-have-delivered-magnetic-material-to-the-moon/ Asteroids may have delivered magnetic material to the Moon]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magnetic Anomaly}}\n[[Category:Magnetic anomalies| ]]\n[[Category:Geomagnetism]]\n", "name_user": "Vk.alberta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInterpretation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_anomaly"}
{"title_page": "Sans fil (newspaper)", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Sans fil\n| logo                 = \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = Daily\n| format               = \n| owners               = \n| founder              = \n| publisher            = \n| editor               =\n| chiefeditor          = \n| assoceditor          = \n| maneditor            = \n| newseditor           = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| campuseditor         = \n| campuschief          = \n| opeditor             = \n| sportseditor         = \n| photoeditor          = \n| seniorstaff          =\n| staff                = \n| foundation           = 1922\n| political            =\n| language             = [[French language]]\n| ceased publication   = \n| relaunched           = \n| headquarters         = 4, rue du Faubourg, [[Montmartre]], [[Paris]] {{Coord|48|52|18.5|N|2|20|35.4|E}}<ref name=\"p2\"/>\n| circulation          = \n| sister newspapers    =\n| ISSN                 = \n| oclc                 = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Sans fil''''' was a daily newspaper published from [[Paris]], [[France]], founded in 1922. The newspaper was published by the \"Sans Fil\" Information Agency. As of the mid-1930s, Albert Ebingre served as general director of the newspaper and Victor Pardon as its editor-in-chief. Key contributors included Egdar Allix (Professor of Law) and Bastid (Member of Parliament, head of the Foreign Affairs Commission).<ref name=\"p2\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=IlnQAAAAMAAJ Nomenclature des journaux & revues en langue fran\u00e7aise du monde entier]''. Paris, Les bureaux de l'Argus, 1937. p. 54</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|France}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1922 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1922]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:Publications with year of disestablishment missing]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Sans fil\n| logo                 = \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = Daily\n| format               = \n| owners               = \n| founder              = \n| publisher            = \n| editor               =\n| chiefeditor          = \n| assoceditor          = \n| maneditor            = \n| newseditor           = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| campuseditor         = \n| campuschief          = \n| opeditor             = \n| sportseditor         = \n| photoeditor          = \n| seniorstaff          =\n| staff                = \n| foundation           = 1922\n| political            =\n| language             = [[French language]]\n| ceased publication   = \n| relaunched           = \n| headquarters         = 4, rue du Faubourg, [[Montmartre]], [[Paris]] {{Coord|48|52|18.5|N|2|20|35.4|E}}<ref name=\"p2\"/>\n| circulation          = \n| sister newspapers    =\n| ISSN                 = \n| oclc                 = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Sans fil''''' was a daily newspaper published from [[Paris]], [[France]], founded in 1922. The newspaper was published by the \"Sans Fil\" Information Agency. As of the mid-1930s, Albert Ebingre served as general director of the newspaper and Victor Pardon as its editor-in-chief. Key contributors included Egdar Allix (Professor of Law) and Bastid (Member of Parliament, head of the Foreign Affairs Commission).<ref name=\"p2\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=IlnQAAAAMAAJ Nomenclature des journaux & revues en langue fran\u00e7aise du monde entier]''. Paris, Les bureaux de l'Argus, 1937. p. 54</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|France}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1922 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Publications established